WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:10.700
[Amit Varma]: There's an old cliche about no matter what truth you discover about India, the opposite

00:00:10.700 --> 00:00:11.700
[Amit Varma]: is also true.

00:00:11.700 --> 00:00:16.780
[Amit Varma]: I've always argued that India has always been deeply illiberal and my main piece of

00:00:16.780 --> 00:00:19.780
[Amit Varma]: evidence for this is the way women are treated.

00:00:19.780 --> 00:00:25.160
[Amit Varma]: Indian culture is unquestionably sexist and even in the year 2020, most women are second

00:00:25.160 --> 00:00:30.680
[Amit Varma]: class citizens in India and yet Indian history is littered with badass women.

00:00:30.680 --> 00:00:36.080
[Amit Varma]: Some of them are outliers operating despite social constraints, but many of them were

00:00:36.080 --> 00:00:41.840
[Amit Varma]: enabled by social norms, particularly in Kerala, where for centuries a matrilineal system made

00:00:41.840 --> 00:00:46.460
[Amit Varma]: women the dominant figures in their households with men taking a backseat.

00:00:46.460 --> 00:00:50.720
[Amit Varma]: And very often the women who have stepped forward to take charge have proved themselves

00:00:50.720 --> 00:00:53.880
[Amit Varma]: to be capable of leading from the front.

00:00:53.880 --> 00:00:56.440
[Amit Varma]: Let's shift the lens for just a moment to the present.

00:00:56.440 --> 00:01:02.000
[Amit Varma]: At the time of recording this episode on January 16, 2020, protests have been raging against

00:01:02.000 --> 00:01:04.880
[Amit Varma]: the Citizenship Amendment Act for a few weeks now.

00:01:04.880 --> 00:01:09.760
[Amit Varma]: These are mostly spontaneous protests erupting from below instead of being managed from the

00:01:09.760 --> 00:01:10.760
[Amit Varma]: top.

00:01:10.760 --> 00:01:15.920
[Amit Varma]: And it's especially striking to me how many women have come forward to lead the charge.

00:01:15.920 --> 00:01:19.360
[Amit Varma]: Maybe these women will lead us towards more freedom.

00:01:19.360 --> 00:01:24.240
[Amit Varma]: And if they need to search for inspiration, all they have to do is look south towards

00:01:24.240 --> 00:01:25.240
[Amit Varma]: Travancore.

00:01:25.240 --> 00:01:31.240
[Unknown]: Welcome to the scene and the unseen.

00:01:31.240 --> 00:01:35.320
[Unknown]: Our weekly podcast on economics, politics, and behavioral science.

00:01:35.320 --> 00:01:40.160
[Unknown]: Please welcome your host, Amit Verma.

00:01:40.160 --> 00:01:41.380
[Amit Varma]: Welcome to the scene and the unseen.

00:01:41.380 --> 00:01:47.160
[Amit Varma]: My guest in today's episode is a young historian, Manu Pillay, and we'll be discussing his first

00:01:47.160 --> 00:01:49.280
[Amit Varma]: book, The Ivory Throne.

00:01:49.280 --> 00:01:50.640
[Guest]: Manu, welcome to the show.

00:01:50.640 --> 00:01:51.640
[Guest]: Thank you for having me again.

00:01:51.640 --> 00:01:53.320
[Amit Varma]: This is, I think, the third time.

00:01:53.320 --> 00:01:54.440
[Amit Varma]: This is the third time, yeah.

00:01:54.440 --> 00:01:59.280
[Amit Varma]: And we have actually in the past discussed how you kind of got drawn to history and stuff.

00:01:59.280 --> 00:02:01.360
[Amit Varma]: But I'm going to ask you again, because this is your first book.

00:02:01.360 --> 00:02:06.280
[Amit Varma]: So in the context of your book, it's sort of worth asking, you know, why this subject

00:02:06.280 --> 00:02:11.200
[Amit Varma]: and did you want to be a historian or did history happen to you after you decided you

00:02:11.200 --> 00:02:12.200
[Amit Varma]: want to do this book?

00:02:12.200 --> 00:02:15.400
[Guest]: You know, history happened because of the stories, you know, as I've said before, I

00:02:15.400 --> 00:02:19.280
[Guest]: think, in one of your earlier episodes, and I recently wrote an essay about it, about

00:02:19.280 --> 00:02:23.840
[Guest]: my great-great-grandparents, who were both divorcees in the 1880s, both members of this,

00:02:23.840 --> 00:02:28.680
[Guest]: you know, so-called high caste Sanskritic universe, you know, both are very well educated.

00:02:28.680 --> 00:02:30.800
[Guest]: They were both from landlord families and so on.

00:02:30.800 --> 00:02:34.280
[Guest]: And you would imagine, at least my textbooks gave me the impression that, you know, people

00:02:34.280 --> 00:02:36.280
[Guest]: like this were patriarchal families.

00:02:36.280 --> 00:02:37.440
[Guest]: There was no concept of divorce.

00:02:37.440 --> 00:02:40.600
[Guest]: On the other hand, only widowhood could end a marriage for a woman.

00:02:40.600 --> 00:02:43.920
[Guest]: But, you know, then I'd go back to Kerala and discover that the opposite was the case

00:02:43.920 --> 00:02:45.480
[Guest]: with my great-great-grandmother.

00:02:45.480 --> 00:02:49.280
[Guest]: She was not only a divorcee in her teens, really, she got married, I think, at 13 the

00:02:49.280 --> 00:02:51.120
[Guest]: first time.

00:02:51.120 --> 00:02:52.120
[Guest]: She got pregnant.

00:02:52.120 --> 00:02:55.320
[Guest]: She was deeply in love with her husband, who was a Brahmin, which again, you know, it's

00:02:55.320 --> 00:02:59.880
[Guest]: an inter-caste union, which is where Brahmin men could marry Naira women back in the day.

00:02:59.880 --> 00:03:00.880
[Guest]: And she got pregnant.

00:03:00.880 --> 00:03:03.600
[Guest]: It was a female child, but it was a stillbirth.

00:03:03.600 --> 00:03:06.640
[Guest]: So when this poor Brahmin came afterwards to collect his wife and child and take them

00:03:06.640 --> 00:03:10.840
[Guest]: to his place, Raman's mother-in-law stopped him at the threshold and said, you know, the

00:03:10.840 --> 00:03:14.000
[Guest]: baby was a girl, and because the baby died, there's something wrong with you.

00:03:14.000 --> 00:03:17.560
[Guest]: It's a little bit like in North India, women are blamed for the children they produce.

00:03:17.560 --> 00:03:21.240
[Guest]: If they produce female children, you know, it's not considered a good thing, at least

00:03:21.240 --> 00:03:23.680
[Guest]: in very many rural orthodox families.

00:03:23.680 --> 00:03:25.720
[Guest]: Whereas here, it was the other way around.

00:03:25.720 --> 00:03:30.120
[Guest]: The man was blamed for, you know, having a dead baby girl, because in a matrilineal family,

00:03:30.120 --> 00:03:33.280
[Guest]: the death of a female child is considered a bad woman.

00:03:33.280 --> 00:03:37.440
[Guest]: So the husband was told to go back, never come back, and the marriage was dissolved.

00:03:37.440 --> 00:03:40.880
[Guest]: And even when we were kids, there was a stone there where, you know, we were often told

00:03:40.880 --> 00:03:44.040
[Guest]: that he sat on that stone and he wept for an hour before he left.

00:03:44.040 --> 00:03:47.440
[Guest]: And some 33 years later, when he was dying, he was on his deathbed.

00:03:47.440 --> 00:03:52.640
[Guest]: He actually sent a servant to express the desire to meet this first wife of his after

00:03:52.640 --> 00:03:54.000
[Guest]: over three decades.

00:03:54.000 --> 00:03:56.920
[Guest]: She didn't go, but three of her children actually went and met him.

00:03:56.920 --> 00:04:00.320
[Guest]: And I thought this was a fascinating thing that, you know, you're not only a divorce

00:04:00.320 --> 00:04:04.760
[Guest]: in the 1880s, your first husband dies three decades later, and your children go to meet

00:04:04.760 --> 00:04:09.560
[Guest]: your their mother's first husband, and the second husband agrees to let his children

00:04:09.560 --> 00:04:13.440
[Guest]: go and meet his wife's first husband and things like that, completely challenged everything

00:04:13.440 --> 00:04:16.600
[Guest]: I had been reading in my textbooks growing up in Maharashtra.

00:04:16.600 --> 00:04:20.520
[Guest]: I'm sure in Kerala, people are slightly more aware of this if they grow up there.

00:04:20.520 --> 00:04:24.440
[Guest]: But for me, I think, you know, listening to stories like this was my first introduction

00:04:24.440 --> 00:04:25.440
[Guest]: to the matrilineal system.

00:04:25.440 --> 00:04:30.000
[Guest]: And I was always struck that, you know, this needed some kind of a wider dissemination.

00:04:30.000 --> 00:04:31.640
[Guest]: There was a lot of scholarly work on it.

00:04:31.640 --> 00:04:34.440
[Guest]: There is a lot of feminist work on the matrilineal system.

00:04:34.440 --> 00:04:37.720
[Guest]: But I thought someone needs to disseminate it to a larger audience.

00:04:37.720 --> 00:04:42.280
[Amit Varma]: So is it fair to say that your desire to write the book came partly because no one had written

00:04:42.280 --> 00:04:46.260
[Amit Varma]: this and you wanted to write it in a sense, because this is a book you would have wanted

00:04:46.260 --> 00:04:47.260
[Guest]: to read?

00:04:47.260 --> 00:04:50.640
[Guest]: You know, I mean, I was doing a lot of reading on Kerala history, you know, I was doing a

00:04:50.640 --> 00:04:55.000
[Guest]: lot of reading on academic books and you know, historical work, etc.

00:04:55.000 --> 00:04:58.520
[Guest]: Somewhere in 2018, I came across the name of Sethu Lakshmibai, who's the protagonist

00:04:58.520 --> 00:04:59.520
[Guest]: of the ivory throne.

00:04:59.520 --> 00:05:03.840
[Guest]: And I thought, you know, there's only one photograph of her with a little daughter in

00:05:03.840 --> 00:05:06.320
[Guest]: that picture, which I could find online.

00:05:06.320 --> 00:05:09.520
[Guest]: In all the history books, she's mentioned briefly, but then very quickly people move

00:05:09.520 --> 00:05:11.480
[Guest]: on to the next ruler.

00:05:11.480 --> 00:05:15.520
[Guest]: And I discovered that, you know, all these rulers, there was a lot of general, you know,

00:05:15.520 --> 00:05:18.680
[Guest]: all about everybody was very much about how they were good for development, how they were

00:05:18.680 --> 00:05:23.320
[Guest]: all very progressive and simple and so on, and not like your usual image of an Indian

00:05:23.320 --> 00:05:24.320
[Guest]: Maharaja.

00:05:24.320 --> 00:05:26.200
[Guest]: Of course, slightly exaggerated that they were so simple.

00:05:26.200 --> 00:05:27.200
[Guest]: They weren't.

00:05:27.200 --> 00:05:28.200
[Guest]: They were royalty.

00:05:28.200 --> 00:05:29.200
[Guest]: Royalty is never all that simple.

00:05:29.200 --> 00:05:34.160
[Guest]: But I was always curious as to why this lady was sort of footnoted, why she never made

00:05:34.160 --> 00:05:39.720
[Guest]: it to that kind of a mainstream recognizability in terms of public intervention in Kerala

00:05:39.720 --> 00:05:40.720
[Guest]: elsewhere.

00:05:40.720 --> 00:05:43.560
[Guest]: Nobody really, they vaguely knew her name, but they didn't know what happened to her.

00:05:43.560 --> 00:05:46.080
[Guest]: And most mysteriously, she had a little girl in that photograph.

00:05:46.080 --> 00:05:51.160
[Guest]: There was one article in the Hindu back in 2008, which had this photo of her and this

00:05:51.160 --> 00:05:52.160
[Guest]: little baby girl.

00:05:52.160 --> 00:05:54.040
[Guest]: And I kept thinking it's the matrilineal system.

00:05:54.040 --> 00:05:57.800
[Guest]: So that girl's descendants are members of the ex-royal family of Travancore, where did

00:05:57.800 --> 00:05:59.920
[Guest]: they disappear because they didn't live in Trivandrum.

00:05:59.920 --> 00:06:04.120
[Guest]: The family that lived in Trivandrum was another branch from Sethu Lakshmibai's sister, Sethu

00:06:04.120 --> 00:06:07.000
[Guest]: Parvati Bai, who is the, let's say, antagonist of the book.

00:06:07.000 --> 00:06:08.000
[Amit Varma]: Junior Rani.

00:06:08.000 --> 00:06:09.000
[Amit Varma]: Junior Rani.

00:06:09.000 --> 00:06:10.600
[Guest]: So it's Senior Rani and Junior Rani.

00:06:10.600 --> 00:06:12.640
[Guest]: So what happened to the Senior Rani's family?

00:06:12.640 --> 00:06:16.400
[Guest]: So you know, the moment I started asking questions about Sethu Lakshmibai, I started asking other

00:06:16.400 --> 00:06:20.360
[Guest]: people, you know, what happened to this lady, a lot of elders, including a great uncle in

00:06:20.360 --> 00:06:24.360
[Guest]: my family, who's now 99 years old, he said, oh, you know, if you ask questions about that,

00:06:24.360 --> 00:06:27.160
[Guest]: you're going to stumble on a lot of mischievous material.

00:06:27.160 --> 00:06:28.360
[Guest]: You shouldn't go down that route.

00:06:28.360 --> 00:06:30.280
[Guest]: It's not a good story.

00:06:30.280 --> 00:06:33.560
[Guest]: And actually, when you're 18 years old, and you're told not to do something, you're obviously

00:06:33.560 --> 00:06:38.040
[Guest]: going to do the exact opposite and start digging up what you're not supposed to dig up.

00:06:38.040 --> 00:06:40.480
[Guest]: So I think that's how I started asking questions.

00:06:40.480 --> 00:06:43.880
[Guest]: And initially, I came across some material, I got in touch over Facebook with one of her

00:06:43.880 --> 00:06:48.080
[Guest]: family members, they sent me a book they privately published, containing all her letters and

00:06:48.080 --> 00:06:49.560
[Guest]: private papers.

00:06:49.560 --> 00:06:53.200
[Guest]: And once they sent this to me, I was fascinated by the story, fascinated by the tragedy really

00:06:53.200 --> 00:06:58.640
[Guest]: in many ways, and even by her personality, you know, the kind of life arc she had.

00:06:58.640 --> 00:07:02.720
[Guest]: And I wrote, I think at that time with a basic sort of reading with some books and this material

00:07:02.720 --> 00:07:03.720
[Guest]: from the letters, etc.

00:07:03.720 --> 00:07:07.740
[Guest]: I got, I wrote a blog, I had, you know, in 2008, it was the age of blogs.

00:07:07.740 --> 00:07:11.680
[Guest]: And I had a blog that perhaps five people read, five people I knew, who were also interested

00:07:11.680 --> 00:07:13.120
[Guest]: in Kerala history.

00:07:13.120 --> 00:07:17.640
[Guest]: But this particular article about her talking about her somewhat tragic life and career,

00:07:17.640 --> 00:07:22.440
[Guest]: and the way it ended on a very sad note, it brought me this barrage of trolling in 2008.

00:07:22.440 --> 00:07:24.360
[Guest]: 2008 trolling wasn't a big deal.

00:07:24.360 --> 00:07:28.080
[Guest]: But suddenly, there was like a heap of messages, comments under this blog saying, how dare

00:07:28.080 --> 00:07:29.080
[Guest]: you write this?

00:07:29.080 --> 00:07:30.080
[Guest]: This is all lies.

00:07:30.080 --> 00:07:31.080
[Guest]: This is impossible.

00:07:31.080 --> 00:07:34.680
[Guest]: And one even rather casteist remark by one man saying, you know, we were kings back in

00:07:34.680 --> 00:07:38.320
[Guest]: the day, who belongs to that royal community, not the family, saying, you know, back in

00:07:38.320 --> 00:07:41.520
[Guest]: the day, if you'd have written something like this, your head would have been chopped off.

00:07:41.520 --> 00:07:45.360
[Guest]: And I was like, you know, at 18, I was like, my God, what is it about this woman that triggers

00:07:45.360 --> 00:07:47.880
[Guest]: such, you know, animosity and hatred?

00:07:47.880 --> 00:07:53.120
[Guest]: Why is it that telling her story as it is, seems to provoke so much angst and hate from

00:07:53.120 --> 00:07:56.040
[Guest]: all these unknown people I've never met on the internet, and who had never come to my

00:07:56.040 --> 00:07:59.000
[Guest]: blog before they heard that there was such an article on her.

00:07:59.000 --> 00:08:02.920
[Guest]: That's when I started deciding that, you know, I had decided to sort of start digging up

00:08:02.920 --> 00:08:07.800
[Guest]: her story a little more, you know, discovering more details, trying to find out what exactly

00:08:07.800 --> 00:08:09.160
[Guest]: the story was.

00:08:09.160 --> 00:08:14.080
[Guest]: And that started really in 2009, and took me to 2015 to finish the ivory throne.

00:08:14.080 --> 00:08:18.400
[Amit Varma]: And did you decide at that point that you're going to write a book or was it just no, I

00:08:18.400 --> 00:08:21.160
[Guest]: was more interested in looking up the story.

00:08:21.160 --> 00:08:24.120
[Guest]: But somewhere along the way turned into a book because I realized there was no book

00:08:24.120 --> 00:08:25.120
[Guest]: on her.

00:08:25.120 --> 00:08:27.320
[Guest]: I mean, her granddaughter published this book of letters and so on.

00:08:27.320 --> 00:08:32.400
[Guest]: But there was no biography as it were, there was no Travancore history written in a revisionist

00:08:32.400 --> 00:08:33.400
[Guest]: style.

00:08:33.400 --> 00:08:36.440
[Guest]: You know, most people may not know that, you know, in North India, for example, other parts

00:08:36.440 --> 00:08:39.680
[Guest]: of India, Travancore history is not really something you think about.

00:08:39.680 --> 00:08:43.660
[Guest]: But in Kerala, it's a pretty big deal, because that was Kerala's premier princely state.

00:08:43.660 --> 00:08:47.400
[Guest]: It had a major role in the culture and in the political evolution of the state, a lot

00:08:47.400 --> 00:08:49.600
[Guest]: of the parties, you know, the rise of communism, etc.

00:08:49.600 --> 00:08:53.840
[Guest]: It's linked to a great extent to Travancore and the policies of the last Diwan of Travancore.

00:08:53.840 --> 00:08:56.320
[Guest]: So Travancore was a big deal in Kerala history.

00:08:56.320 --> 00:09:01.400
[Guest]: So I was just, you know, keen to sort of fill this gap where this lady was concerned.

00:09:01.400 --> 00:09:06.440
[Guest]: And that I think, I think I wrote my first draft of the book by 2011-12.

00:09:06.440 --> 00:09:08.440
[Guest]: And frankly, at that time, I thought it was ready to publish.

00:09:08.440 --> 00:09:11.800
[Guest]: I'm glad I didn't because it would have been a hideous book that would have sunk without

00:09:11.800 --> 00:09:12.800
[Guest]: a trace.

00:09:12.800 --> 00:09:16.720
[Guest]: So it took another three and a half years to, you know, get to beat it into shape to

00:09:16.720 --> 00:09:21.120
[Guest]: get more material to really research and put the pieces together, which took me to, you

00:09:21.120 --> 00:09:24.320
[Guest]: know, there's material from America, which I couldn't find in India for there's this

00:09:24.320 --> 00:09:28.680
[Guest]: obscure magazine that I was looking for a journal that covered specifically the princely

00:09:28.680 --> 00:09:32.640
[Guest]: states, which was a massive source of information, because every two weeks, they had material

00:09:32.640 --> 00:09:35.920
[Guest]: on different princely states and what was happening, couldn't find it in India couldn't

00:09:35.920 --> 00:09:39.320
[Guest]: find it in Britain finally ended up finding it in America.

00:09:39.320 --> 00:09:43.920
[Guest]: And, you know, I had to spend a bomb to acquire that material, a lot from the British archives,

00:09:43.920 --> 00:09:48.160
[Guest]: then from the Delhi archives, the Kerala state archives, interviews with lots of people,

00:09:48.160 --> 00:09:52.640
[Guest]: you know, because the protagonist and the antagonist both died in the 1980s, which meant

00:09:52.640 --> 00:09:55.280
[Guest]: that people who knew them, their children, they were still alive at that time.

00:09:55.280 --> 00:09:59.560
[Guest]: So I had to go talk to them, you know, and it was interesting to sort of go through that

00:09:59.560 --> 00:10:04.320
[Guest]: journey for five, six years, and put together the story.

00:10:04.320 --> 00:10:08.560
[Guest]: Since then, you know, that book has not only filled a gap, I think, to my great advantage

00:10:08.560 --> 00:10:10.080
[Guest]: in terms of sales, etc.

00:10:10.080 --> 00:10:13.680
[Guest]: Anytime anybody looks up Kerala on Amazon, or Flipkart or whatever, this is the first

00:10:13.680 --> 00:10:15.080
[Guest]: book that pops up.

00:10:15.080 --> 00:10:18.480
[Guest]: Because there hasn't been a big mainstream book on Kerala for a very long time.

00:10:18.480 --> 00:10:22.320
[Guest]: There are academic books, there are books in Kerala, but for a larger pan Indian English

00:10:22.320 --> 00:10:25.840
[Guest]: reading audience, there hasn't been that much for a very long time.

00:10:25.840 --> 00:10:30.240
[Guest]: So anybody who now wants a book on Kerala history, this sort of shows up as the first

00:10:30.240 --> 00:10:31.240
[Guest]: option they have.

00:10:31.240 --> 00:10:33.320
[Guest]: And that's great for me in terms of sales.

00:10:33.320 --> 00:10:38.600
[Guest]: And I'm glad that the book helped resurrect Setulakshmi Bai and put her back in public

00:10:38.600 --> 00:10:40.600
[Amit Varma]: imagination, because she deserves to be there.

00:10:40.600 --> 00:10:45.040
[Amit Varma]: And the book's also been optioned, I believe, for a potential web series.

00:10:45.040 --> 00:10:48.480
[Guest]: People keep saying film, but I think it's too big to be a film.

00:10:48.480 --> 00:10:53.000
[Guest]: The drama is far too intense to cover it in one two hour film, it'll end up being a shoddy

00:10:53.000 --> 00:10:56.440
[Amit Varma]: job if it's a film, I think, I can't really do justice to the story.

00:10:56.440 --> 00:11:01.880
[Amit Varma]: And in contrast with the books you've spoken about in our previous episodes, but the ones

00:11:01.880 --> 00:11:06.080
[Amit Varma]: that you wrote after this, there are no marauding elephants, there are runaway elephants in

00:11:06.080 --> 00:11:09.920
[Amit Varma]: one scene where somebody goes to a function and the elephants have run away.

00:11:09.920 --> 00:11:15.160
[Amit Varma]: But there is much less bloodshed, but perhaps more human drama.

00:11:15.160 --> 00:11:19.580
[Amit Varma]: So did you want to be a historian before you actually set upon this quest or did setting

00:11:19.580 --> 00:11:21.960
[Guest]: upon this quest naturally make you a historian?

00:11:21.960 --> 00:11:25.600
[Guest]: Yeah, I think it's the second way, which is that, you know, once I started the book, once

00:11:25.600 --> 00:11:29.960
[Guest]: I started doing my research, it also coincided with my master's degree in London, the fact

00:11:29.960 --> 00:11:33.200
[Guest]: of the matter was that I only persuaded my parents to let me go there because I wanted

00:11:33.200 --> 00:11:34.320
[Guest]: the archives.

00:11:34.320 --> 00:11:37.700
[Guest]: And you can't really tell your parents that, you know, you want them to spend a bomb and

00:11:37.700 --> 00:11:42.080
[Guest]: send you abroad, if you write a book, no parent in India is going to allow that.

00:11:42.080 --> 00:11:46.320
[Guest]: So what was interesting was research methods, we were taught for my master's program for

00:11:46.320 --> 00:11:50.280
[Guest]: the thesis, you know, how to understand the archives, how to negotiate libraries and so

00:11:50.280 --> 00:11:53.460
[Guest]: on, I could apply that almost immediately to my own research.

00:11:53.460 --> 00:11:56.400
[Guest]: And once I started doing that, you know, I had another career that I used to work in

00:11:56.400 --> 00:11:59.960
[Guest]: Parliament first, then I worked in the British Parliament for a while, then I worked with

00:11:59.960 --> 00:12:01.560
[Guest]: the BBC for a while.

00:12:01.560 --> 00:12:05.920
[Guest]: But it was the book and then the success of the book that really got me thinking and I

00:12:05.920 --> 00:12:08.000
[Guest]: was like, you know, this is something I'm passionate about.

00:12:08.000 --> 00:12:12.560
[Guest]: I am interested in history, I enjoy the research, I enjoy sitting in archives and libraries

00:12:12.560 --> 00:12:17.160
[Guest]: and discovering, you know, things and I enjoy also, I think, bringing to the fore marginalized

00:12:17.160 --> 00:12:21.960
[Guest]: stories, all the, both my first and my second book, they're both about, you know, either

00:12:21.960 --> 00:12:26.360
[Guest]: figures who are marginalized or a region that is marginalized that doesn't get the attention

00:12:26.360 --> 00:12:30.540
[Guest]: it perhaps deserves in terms of Indian history, as we talk in general.

00:12:30.540 --> 00:12:34.240
[Guest]: So I think that triggered this desire to keep focusing on history.

00:12:34.240 --> 00:12:38.520
[Guest]: And now I've taken the plunge, now I've become a full time writer and, you know, researcher.

00:12:38.520 --> 00:12:43.200
[Guest]: So now there's no escaping with the consequences of what I have brought upon myself.

00:12:43.200 --> 00:12:47.640
[Guest]: So far it's worked out, but I'm under no impression that this, you know, you never know what the

00:12:47.640 --> 00:12:48.640
[Guest]: future holds.

00:12:48.640 --> 00:12:52.280
[Guest]: Three successful books does not mean that your fourth or fifth or sixth will always

00:12:52.280 --> 00:12:57.160
[Guest]: be a successful book seem to be prepared for the worst, but I've decided to take that gamble

00:12:57.160 --> 00:12:58.720
[Amit Varma]: and you know, take that risk.

00:12:58.720 --> 00:13:03.480
[Amit Varma]: No, in fact, whenever the subject of you has come up in my conversations with other people,

00:13:03.480 --> 00:13:07.760
[Amit Varma]: all of them basically have the tone of how dare that scoundrel write three books before

00:13:07.760 --> 00:13:08.760
[Amit Varma]: the age of 30.

00:13:08.760 --> 00:13:11.200
[Amit Varma]: Has he even started shaving?

00:13:11.200 --> 00:13:16.680
[Amit Varma]: How do older historians respond to what in their eyes must be this young kid just coming

00:13:16.680 --> 00:13:18.160
[Amit Varma]: up and churning out book after book?

00:13:18.160 --> 00:13:21.080
[Guest]: You know, older historians have strangely been very generous.

00:13:21.080 --> 00:13:24.920
[Guest]: Actually one advantage is that, look at the books now, the first one won the Sahitya Academy

00:13:24.920 --> 00:13:25.920
[Guest]: is Yuva Purushkar.

00:13:25.920 --> 00:13:28.400
[Guest]: It was given by a panel of very distinguished scholars.

00:13:28.400 --> 00:13:31.560
[Guest]: And two years later, I actually ran into one of the jury members who told me who I was

00:13:31.560 --> 00:13:32.560
[Guest]: up against.

00:13:32.560 --> 00:13:33.680
[Guest]: And I'm not allowed to name the person.

00:13:33.680 --> 00:13:37.240
[Guest]: But it was very flattering to discover that, you know, I won despite that person being

00:13:37.240 --> 00:13:39.880
[Guest]: in the list and in the running for the award.

00:13:39.880 --> 00:13:43.560
[Guest]: Second book was not only, you know, critically acclaimed, it was also reviewed glowingly

00:13:43.560 --> 00:13:45.480
[Guest]: in a peer reviewed academic journal.

00:13:45.480 --> 00:13:49.200
[Guest]: For me, I'm doing my PhD now, you know, I, although I want to bridge the academic world

00:13:49.200 --> 00:13:54.480
[Guest]: with a larger audience, you always have this fear, you know, are you are you somehow diluting

00:13:54.480 --> 00:13:55.480
[Guest]: historical research?

00:13:55.480 --> 00:13:58.920
[Guest]: Are you somehow are you doing it in the way academics do it, etc.

00:13:58.920 --> 00:14:02.000
[Guest]: So it's good to be in a peer reviewed academic journal, because that means that your work

00:14:02.000 --> 00:14:03.000
[Amit Varma]: is passed.

00:14:03.000 --> 00:14:04.000
[Guest]: And this was Rebel Sultans.

00:14:04.000 --> 00:14:06.280
[Guest]: This was Rebel Sultans in a journal called Studies in History.

00:14:06.280 --> 00:14:09.800
[Guest]: And it was reviewed by University of Illinois professor and I was actually taken aback.

00:14:09.800 --> 00:14:10.800
[Guest]: I had no idea.

00:14:10.800 --> 00:14:14.180
[Guest]: There was University of Illinois professor reading my work.

00:14:14.180 --> 00:14:18.760
[Guest]: And even the praise, for example, on Rebel Sultans, the first book doesn't have any endorsements

00:14:18.760 --> 00:14:22.400
[Guest]: from any big names, because that's not something I wanted at that time.

00:14:22.400 --> 00:14:23.800
[Guest]: The second book, my publishers were keen.

00:14:23.800 --> 00:14:26.760
[Guest]: So I said, look, you reach out to whoever you're interested in.

00:14:26.760 --> 00:14:30.680
[Guest]: So we reached out to Muzaffar Alam, and he is a very senior scholar, you know, essentially

00:14:30.680 --> 00:14:35.040
[Guest]: the, you know, the big name of North Indian history and Mughal history and even the Deccan.

00:14:35.040 --> 00:14:37.440
[Guest]: He's worked a lot with Sanjay Subramanian.

00:14:37.440 --> 00:14:41.120
[Guest]: And you know, you discover, he basically came back saying he was working on something, so

00:14:41.120 --> 00:14:43.320
[Guest]: he wouldn't have time to go through the manuscript.

00:14:43.320 --> 00:14:47.680
[Guest]: And then, I'm not exaggerating, a day before we went to press, he emailed back saying he'd

00:14:47.680 --> 00:14:51.320
[Guest]: managed to read the manuscript, and he would love to give her an endorsement for the book.

00:14:51.320 --> 00:14:55.000
[Guest]: For me, that was a great, you know, I felt really not only honored, but also somewhat

00:14:55.000 --> 00:14:59.200
[Guest]: more confident, because it's not easy for a Muzaffar Alam to sort of endorse your work.

00:14:59.200 --> 00:15:00.700
[Guest]: He's a very senior scholar.

00:15:00.700 --> 00:15:05.720
[Guest]: He's not the type to take, you know, careless only or lazily written history very seriously.

00:15:05.720 --> 00:15:07.880
[Guest]: So that meant he appreciated it.

00:15:07.880 --> 00:15:10.800
[Guest]: Then my publisher told me that they ran into Rudraksha Mukherjee, who was also a very big

00:15:10.800 --> 00:15:11.800
[Guest]: historian.

00:15:11.800 --> 00:15:12.800
[Guest]: He appreciated the book.

00:15:12.800 --> 00:15:16.200
[Guest]: And now for the paperback edition, I think he's giving us an endorsement as well.

00:15:16.200 --> 00:15:22.840
[Guest]: So I think for me, having these big historians sort of support my work and encourage it is

00:15:22.840 --> 00:15:24.740
[Guest]: something I value a great deal.

00:15:24.740 --> 00:15:28.520
[Guest]: And I think it, going see, you always make mistakes, you're always, you're always learning

00:15:28.520 --> 00:15:29.520
[Guest]: none of your works.

00:15:29.520 --> 00:15:32.640
[Guest]: I think no historian can confidently say their work is 100% solid.

00:15:32.640 --> 00:15:35.960
[Guest]: You're always learning things are always going to be minor errors and omissions and slips

00:15:35.960 --> 00:15:36.960
[Guest]: and so on.

00:15:36.960 --> 00:15:37.960
[Guest]: But you keep improving.

00:15:37.960 --> 00:15:41.840
[Guest]: So I think it's good to have older historians sort of support that.

00:15:41.840 --> 00:15:46.080
[Guest]: What where some opposition has come, interestingly, from some of my contemporaries.

00:15:46.080 --> 00:15:51.120
[Guest]: So a lot of my PhD colleagues in London, most of them, I mean, the ones from India, at least,

00:15:51.120 --> 00:15:52.400
[Guest]: they sort of frown upon this.

00:15:52.400 --> 00:15:56.800
[Guest]: I don't know if it's a case of sour grapes, or if it's simply because, you know, they're

00:15:56.800 --> 00:15:58.920
[Guest]: like, no, no, no, you can't do this popular history thing.

00:15:58.920 --> 00:15:59.920
[Guest]: It's a bad idea.

00:15:59.920 --> 00:16:04.040
[Guest]: You know, academia is where you can do it soberly, properly, this making it engaging

00:16:04.040 --> 00:16:09.000
[Guest]: through writing and turn it into a storytelling process is very risky, it's fraught with lots

00:16:09.000 --> 00:16:10.000
[Guest]: of problems.

00:16:10.000 --> 00:16:11.560
[Guest]: And I agree, it's fraught with problems.

00:16:11.560 --> 00:16:15.360
[Guest]: But as you may have noticed, with the first and the second, the third, not so much, but

00:16:15.360 --> 00:16:19.800
[Guest]: the first and the second, it's rich with footnotes, I make sure that all my sources, the footnotes

00:16:19.800 --> 00:16:24.040
[Guest]: themselves sometimes have essay length material in them, because I'm not trying to sort of

00:16:24.040 --> 00:16:26.120
[Guest]: cut down on the academic aspect of it.

00:16:26.120 --> 00:16:29.680
[Guest]: If you read the footnotes, it almost reads like it's part of an academic book.

00:16:29.680 --> 00:16:33.700
[Guest]: It's just the main narrative that I try and make attractive in terms of writing.

00:16:33.700 --> 00:16:35.640
[Guest]: Some people of my age perhaps disapprove.

00:16:35.640 --> 00:16:40.920
[Guest]: But you know, because the older scholars who've established themselves and won their stripes

00:16:40.920 --> 00:16:44.640
[Guest]: and you know, earned their place up there, they've been supportive so far.

00:16:44.640 --> 00:16:48.280
[Guest]: And for me, I think that is, you know, it's a it's a it's a mark of confidence.

00:16:48.280 --> 00:16:53.120
[Guest]: Therefore, even though my contemporaries may sometimes, you know, rant about me on Facebook,

00:16:53.120 --> 00:16:54.120
[Guest]: I can see it, right?

00:16:54.120 --> 00:16:57.080
[Guest]: I can see that they like, you know, how they do this and things like that.

00:16:57.080 --> 00:16:59.960
[Guest]: But you know, I think it's good to know that older people support you.

00:16:59.960 --> 00:17:03.080
[Guest]: So it gives you the strength and the conviction to carry on.

00:17:03.080 --> 00:17:05.560
[Amit Varma]: And also, I don't really get the thing against popular history.

00:17:05.560 --> 00:17:09.760
[Amit Varma]: I mean, the thing is, as long as the history is solid, why should it be a mark against

00:17:09.760 --> 00:17:12.960
[Amit Varma]: it if it's written very well, and therefore sells very well?

00:17:12.960 --> 00:17:14.800
[Guest]: You know, it's an Indian thing.

00:17:14.800 --> 00:17:18.400
[Guest]: Here, we don't have that much popular history by academics, in the Western world, they always

00:17:18.400 --> 00:17:19.400
[Guest]: do it.

00:17:19.400 --> 00:17:23.440
[Guest]: Now, for example, the same people who say that you should not be doing popular history.

00:17:23.440 --> 00:17:27.280
[Guest]: Sunil Khilnani is an academic, you know, he has a PhD, he used to be the head of the India

00:17:27.280 --> 00:17:30.180
[Guest]: Institute in London, which is where I'm doing my PhD now.

00:17:30.180 --> 00:17:31.880
[Guest]: Now he's moved back to an American university.

00:17:31.880 --> 00:17:35.480
[Guest]: He wrote this iconic book called the idea of India in the late 1990s.

00:17:35.480 --> 00:17:39.720
[Guest]: He also did a book and I was his research assistant for that project called Incarnations,

00:17:39.720 --> 00:17:40.720
[Guest]: India through 50 lives.

00:17:40.720 --> 00:17:45.120
[Guest]: So it's 50 personalities, you've taken their profiles, and you've tried to explain a broader

00:17:45.120 --> 00:17:46.680
[Guest]: Indian history through that.

00:17:46.680 --> 00:17:50.040
[Guest]: Now, neither he nor I are scholars on each of these people.

00:17:50.040 --> 00:17:54.080
[Guest]: I mean, you're taking a VK Krishnamenon, for example, you're taking a Buddha, for example,

00:17:54.080 --> 00:17:56.320
[Guest]: I'm not a Buddhist studies person, neither is he.

00:17:56.320 --> 00:18:00.560
[Guest]: We're not great scholars on Krishnamenon, neither is, you know, Dr. Khilnani.

00:18:00.560 --> 00:18:04.560
[Guest]: But the thing is, that does not preclude us from being able to sort of do a decent amount

00:18:04.560 --> 00:18:06.720
[Guest]: of research on it and write about it.

00:18:06.720 --> 00:18:11.560
[Guest]: The argument that you have to be like a supreme expert on everything you touch is I think

00:18:11.560 --> 00:18:15.880
[Guest]: risky because that I mean, it doesn't hold water, Western academics, and he works in

00:18:15.880 --> 00:18:19.800
[Guest]: the Western world, which is why for them, also doing popular history is not at all a

00:18:19.800 --> 00:18:20.800
[Guest]: surprising thing.

00:18:20.800 --> 00:18:24.560
[Guest]: I mean, right now, there's Supriya Gandhi, who's just brought out a book on Dara Shukla,

00:18:24.560 --> 00:18:28.800
[Guest]: the tragic Mughal prince, and a lot of what ifs and you know, romantic stories around

00:18:28.800 --> 00:18:29.800
[Guest]: Dara Shukla.

00:18:29.800 --> 00:18:33.400
[Guest]: And she's done at least from every, you know, bit I've read so far, she's done a very good

00:18:33.400 --> 00:18:37.520
[Guest]: job of negotiating that inaccessible, attractive language.

00:18:37.520 --> 00:18:41.440
[Guest]: So the thing is, Western academics and people in the Western world make the effort to do

00:18:41.440 --> 00:18:42.440
[Guest]: popular history.

00:18:42.440 --> 00:18:47.240
[Guest]: Here, however, academics have not, I think, reached out that much into the popular audience.

00:18:47.240 --> 00:18:51.480
[Guest]: And another crop of historians has grown up who want to proactively touch and reach the

00:18:51.480 --> 00:18:53.400
[Guest]: popular mass.

00:18:53.400 --> 00:18:57.320
[Guest]: And there's that break, therefore, which naturally, you know, breeds its own insecurities and

00:18:57.320 --> 00:18:59.680
[Guest]: competition and rivalries and so on.

00:18:59.680 --> 00:19:00.680
[Guest]: Historians are also human beings.

00:19:00.680 --> 00:19:05.640
[Guest]: It's not like we are about ego clashes and jealousies and rivalries and fears and things

00:19:05.640 --> 00:19:06.640
[Guest]: like that.

00:19:06.640 --> 00:19:09.260
[Guest]: That's very much a part of anything, any human enterprise.

00:19:09.260 --> 00:19:11.240
[Guest]: And that, I think, exists more in India now.

00:19:11.240 --> 00:19:15.380
[Guest]: But, you know, as more and more historians do make the effort, academic historians do

00:19:15.380 --> 00:19:19.240
[Guest]: make the effort to write for a lay audience, I think it's a constructive thing.

00:19:19.240 --> 00:19:22.480
[Guest]: On the one hand, you can't complain that history is being perverted by politicians, on the other

00:19:22.480 --> 00:19:23.840
[Guest]: hand, do nothing about it.

00:19:23.840 --> 00:19:27.240
[Guest]: And if you want to convince the masses, go out to the masses, go out to the intelligent

00:19:27.240 --> 00:19:30.800
[Guest]: reading audience, you know, go out and reach out beyond your seminar circuit.

00:19:30.800 --> 00:19:32.040
[Guest]: I think there is value in that.

00:19:32.040 --> 00:19:36.680
[Guest]: I think, you know, the fighting for good history happens at different levels.

00:19:36.680 --> 00:19:40.600
[Guest]: It's not merely about, you know, sitting in the seminar circuit and issuing papers that

00:19:40.600 --> 00:19:43.540
[Guest]: you and I will read, but not anybody beyond that.

00:19:43.540 --> 00:19:44.540
[Guest]: That has its value.

00:19:44.540 --> 00:19:46.520
[Guest]: It is from that that people like me benefit.

00:19:46.520 --> 00:19:49.960
[Guest]: We learn a great deal from that, but someone has to also connect it for people who are

00:19:49.960 --> 00:19:51.280
[Guest]: not reading the seminar papers.

00:19:51.280 --> 00:19:57.440
[Amit Varma]: And also so much of the politics of the present and indeed so much of the present period is

00:19:57.440 --> 00:20:01.480
[Amit Varma]: influenced by narratives about the past, which makes it all the more important that we examine

00:20:01.480 --> 00:20:08.240
[Amit Varma]: those more deeply and challenge, you know, loosely held assumptions about the past.

00:20:08.240 --> 00:20:12.720
[Amit Varma]: And I was sort of just thinking aloud yesterday, and it struck me that, you know, many people

00:20:12.720 --> 00:20:15.120
[Amit Varma]: call this current government a conservative government.

00:20:15.120 --> 00:20:19.520
[Amit Varma]: But to me, in one sense, they are not conservative, they are radical, because I think what is

00:20:19.520 --> 00:20:24.740
[Amit Varma]: inherent in Indian society is the fact that we are so assimilative, we take influences

00:20:24.740 --> 00:20:31.320
[Amit Varma]: from everywhere, we are actually incredibly tolerant, and that's almost a DNA of our society.

00:20:31.320 --> 00:20:35.440
[Amit Varma]: And that is something that the current government by trying to overturn and by trying to paint

00:20:35.440 --> 00:20:40.640
[Amit Varma]: the world in binaries, is actually performing a radical act which goes against what our

00:20:40.640 --> 00:20:41.640
[Amit Varma]: society is.

00:20:41.640 --> 00:20:45.120
[Amit Varma]: And it struck me again, and I mean, this is a truism, but it struck me again, while reading

00:20:45.120 --> 00:20:50.720
[Amit Varma]: your book that Kerala is actually an exemplar of this, in the sense that Kerala was one

00:20:50.720 --> 00:20:55.320
[Amit Varma]: probably one of the first globalized places in the world, Christianity came to Kerala

00:20:55.320 --> 00:20:59.880
[Amit Varma]: before it hit Europe, as you point out in your book, early Islam came here and it came

00:20:59.880 --> 00:21:04.120
[Amit Varma]: here peacefully and the lifetime of the prophet in the lifetime of the prophet.

00:21:04.120 --> 00:21:12.280
[Amit Varma]: Tell me a little bit about a sort of, you know, like, you quote, right up here at the

00:21:12.280 --> 00:21:19.240
[Amit Varma]: end, in 1607, he writes, quote, there is no place in all of India, where contentment is

00:21:19.240 --> 00:21:23.760
[Amit Varma]: more universal than at Calicut, both on account of the fertility and beauty of the country

00:21:23.760 --> 00:21:27.800
[Amit Varma]: and of the intercourse with the men of all religions who live there in free exercise

00:21:27.800 --> 00:21:29.160
[Amit Varma]: of their own religion.

00:21:29.160 --> 00:21:33.760
[Amit Varma]: It is the busiest and most full of all traffic and commerce in the whole of India.

00:21:33.760 --> 00:21:38.220
[Amit Varma]: It has merchants from all parts of the world, and of all nations and religions, by reason

00:21:38.220 --> 00:21:42.560
[Amit Varma]: of the liberty and security accorded to them there, stop quote.

00:21:42.560 --> 00:21:47.840
[Amit Varma]: And part of this, obviously, is because it's a port, right, and ports have always attracted

00:21:47.840 --> 00:21:48.840
[Guest]: foreigners.

00:21:48.840 --> 00:21:52.120
[Guest]: See, the idea of the foreigner as an alien is not something that port cultures or coastal

00:21:52.120 --> 00:21:56.120
[Guest]: cultures have in general, because trade is the ecosystem that preserves these societies.

00:21:56.120 --> 00:21:58.920
[Guest]: Now look at a lot of this is also linked to geography.

00:21:58.920 --> 00:22:01.240
[Guest]: Now Kerala is the sliver of the Indian coast.

00:22:01.240 --> 00:22:03.920
[Guest]: It's cut off by the Western Ghats from Tamil Nadu, etc.

00:22:03.920 --> 00:22:04.920
[Guest]: It's not easy access.

00:22:04.920 --> 00:22:08.840
[Guest]: You can access through Palakkad, which is up north and then in the south there's via

00:22:08.840 --> 00:22:09.840
[Guest]: Kanyakumari district.

00:22:09.840 --> 00:22:13.480
[Guest]: There's another area, there's another way to access Kerala, or you will access it via

00:22:13.480 --> 00:22:14.480
[Guest]: the coast.

00:22:14.480 --> 00:22:18.320
[Guest]: But for the most part, Kerala sort of cut out from South Indian, from the peninsula

00:22:18.320 --> 00:22:22.560
[Guest]: as it were, which is why even when Vijayanagar was this great, powerful empire in the south

00:22:22.560 --> 00:22:26.760
[Guest]: that practically conquered almost all of the empire, it never really conquered Kerala,

00:22:26.760 --> 00:22:29.440
[Guest]: because it was Kerala was sort of its own zone.

00:22:29.440 --> 00:22:34.000
[Guest]: But it was also a very small area, which meant local economy was not enough to sustain any

00:22:34.000 --> 00:22:39.760
[Guest]: kind of grand civilization or any kind of grand, extraordinarily wealthy society.

00:22:39.760 --> 00:22:41.160
[Guest]: That wealth came from trade.

00:22:41.160 --> 00:22:45.600
[Guest]: It was trade and pepper and calico, calico comes from calicut, fabric, you know, that

00:22:45.600 --> 00:22:48.960
[Guest]: kind of trade that actually generated money for Kerala's kings.

00:22:48.960 --> 00:22:52.920
[Guest]: Even the idea of kingship in Kerala was very different from Tamil Nadu, North India.

00:22:52.920 --> 00:22:56.480
[Guest]: Kings were not kings who had large standing armies and things like that.

00:22:56.480 --> 00:23:00.800
[Guest]: Kings headed a network really of feudal lords, again linked to geography.

00:23:00.800 --> 00:23:03.360
[Guest]: You know, there are 44 rivers in Kerala.

00:23:03.360 --> 00:23:07.200
[Guest]: And we're talking about a time when navigating all this is extremely difficult, you know,

00:23:07.200 --> 00:23:11.840
[Guest]: moving around is extremely difficult, which means that a king will only control his capital

00:23:11.840 --> 00:23:15.800
[Guest]: and the immediate surroundings and a lot of it is based on feudal levies and things like

00:23:15.800 --> 00:23:16.800
[Guest]: that.

00:23:16.800 --> 00:23:19.760
[Guest]: Kings are not, I mean, they had land revenue, but they didn't really depend very much on

00:23:19.760 --> 00:23:23.600
[Guest]: land revenue, because trade brought them in multiples of what they earned through land.

00:23:23.600 --> 00:23:28.160
[Guest]: So kings had an incentive to promote trade, which meant what promoting new people, new

00:23:28.160 --> 00:23:31.120
[Guest]: colors of people, new people of different faiths.

00:23:31.120 --> 00:23:34.160
[Guest]: There are no issues with that because their livelihood depended on it.

00:23:34.160 --> 00:23:36.800
[Guest]: And none of this comes from entirely like noble thoughts.

00:23:36.800 --> 00:23:39.040
[Guest]: It comes because you have gains from it.

00:23:39.040 --> 00:23:43.080
[Guest]: So Arabs, the zamorin of Calicut builds, you know, builds up the city of Calicut, which

00:23:43.080 --> 00:23:46.220
[Guest]: becomes one of the great cities of the trading world.

00:23:46.220 --> 00:23:49.840
[Guest]: One of the reasons is that other rivals of his have Cologne and other places where the

00:23:49.840 --> 00:23:52.160
[Guest]: Jews and the Christians are dominant.

00:23:52.160 --> 00:23:54.360
[Guest]: The Arabs are sort of looking for a place.

00:23:54.360 --> 00:23:56.200
[Guest]: That's when the Calicut is emerging as a new ruler.

00:23:56.200 --> 00:23:59.480
[Guest]: And he says, hold on, you know, I've got this access to the sea, I'll give you very good

00:23:59.480 --> 00:24:00.480
[Guest]: terms of trade.

00:24:00.480 --> 00:24:01.600
[Guest]: I'll give you honesty.

00:24:01.600 --> 00:24:02.600
[Guest]: I won't cheat you.

00:24:02.600 --> 00:24:09.040
[Guest]: I'll give you a very overall make up a setting that invites trade and commerce to the city.

00:24:09.040 --> 00:24:10.440
[Guest]: And that formula works.

00:24:10.440 --> 00:24:13.960
[Guest]: The Arabs start gravitating towards this, the Chinese start gravitating towards it.

00:24:13.960 --> 00:24:16.680
[Guest]: And it's based on certain conditions that the city thrives.

00:24:16.680 --> 00:24:21.640
[Guest]: Naturally, there is a cultural impact on the area itself altogether.

00:24:21.640 --> 00:24:25.000
[Guest]: The Chinese bring in, the Malayalis eat, we cook a lot of our food in what we call China

00:24:25.000 --> 00:24:26.000
[Guest]: Chatti.

00:24:26.000 --> 00:24:27.000
[Guest]: China is China.

00:24:27.000 --> 00:24:28.880
[Guest]: It's the kind of utensil that came from China.

00:24:28.880 --> 00:24:32.520
[Guest]: There are these legends in Kerala where there's this Nambudiri Brahmin, for example, called

00:24:32.520 --> 00:24:37.280
[Guest]: Pandampurathu Namburi and how he, you know, keeps a Chinese merchant's treasure safe for

00:24:37.280 --> 00:24:40.480
[Guest]: a very long time and how the Chinese merchant is very happy.

00:24:40.480 --> 00:24:44.460
[Guest]: So you're meeting a Chinese foreigner with a Kerala Orthodox Nambudiri Brahmin in one

00:24:44.460 --> 00:24:49.400
[Guest]: of Kerala's oldest legends because the foreigner is always present in Kerala's legends.

00:24:49.400 --> 00:24:54.160
[Guest]: Islam is present to the extent that there is this wonderful story called Parai Pettapandirukulam,

00:24:54.160 --> 00:24:59.280
[Guest]: which is the, it's about a Dalit woman, a Paraya woman, practically one of the lowest

00:24:59.280 --> 00:25:04.240
[Guest]: castes who marries the sage Vararuchi through this adventure of their own.

00:25:04.240 --> 00:25:05.560
[Guest]: And they have 12 children.

00:25:05.560 --> 00:25:10.360
[Guest]: The 12 children includes one daughter from which a major matrilineal Naya family is descended,

00:25:10.360 --> 00:25:14.960
[Guest]: the Kalapara Mupil Nayas, but it also includes a Brahmin, the Meratola Agnihotri.

00:25:14.960 --> 00:25:17.840
[Guest]: It also includes a carpenter called Perindachan.

00:25:17.840 --> 00:25:22.480
[Guest]: It also includes a Dalit man who actually brings, every time the siblings meet for feast,

00:25:22.480 --> 00:25:26.160
[Guest]: this is the man who brings beef, the udders of a cow to this feast, to where a Brahmin

00:25:26.160 --> 00:25:28.040
[Guest]: brother and the woman and all are present.

00:25:28.040 --> 00:25:30.720
[Guest]: There's also a Muslim son and there's a son who's a deity.

00:25:30.720 --> 00:25:36.080
[Guest]: So these 12 children represent different castes, different religions even, and different ways

00:25:36.080 --> 00:25:37.080
[Guest]: of life.

00:25:37.080 --> 00:25:38.760
[Guest]: There's orthodox Brahminical vegetarian life.

00:25:38.760 --> 00:25:41.260
[Guest]: There is somebody who eats the udders of a cow.

00:25:41.260 --> 00:25:46.120
[Guest]: Everybody's represented in that one story of a Brahmin man and a Paraya woman producing

00:25:46.120 --> 00:25:49.720
[Guest]: the 12 castes and the 12 children and so on.

00:25:49.720 --> 00:25:52.680
[Guest]: These legends are basically hinting at something of great value.

00:25:52.680 --> 00:25:57.320
[Guest]: There are texts like the Kerala Olpatti, which is considered the premier text that explains

00:25:57.320 --> 00:25:58.800
[Guest]: the origins of Kerala.

00:25:58.800 --> 00:26:00.840
[Guest]: It's not really a historically sound text.

00:26:00.840 --> 00:26:02.800
[Guest]: It was written somewhere in the 17th century.

00:26:02.800 --> 00:26:04.520
[Guest]: Some say even in the 18th century.

00:26:04.520 --> 00:26:07.880
[Guest]: There's already foreign wars referred to in that with the Portuguese and people like that,

00:26:07.880 --> 00:26:10.160
[Guest]: depending on which version of the Kerala Olpatti you read.

00:26:10.160 --> 00:26:16.240
[Guest]: The oldest political legend of Kerala is about this king called Cheraman Perumal, who converts

00:26:16.240 --> 00:26:17.880
[Guest]: to Islam and goes off to Mecca.

00:26:17.880 --> 00:26:21.080
[Guest]: So you know, in the oldest political legend of Kerala, there is already Islam and there's

00:26:21.080 --> 00:26:22.360
[Guest]: already Arabia.

00:26:22.360 --> 00:26:24.680
[Guest]: So this is the ecosystem in which it works.

00:26:24.680 --> 00:26:28.280
[Guest]: It was easier to cross the Arabian Sea and reach Kerala than for a Malayali to travel

00:26:28.280 --> 00:26:31.240
[Guest]: by land all the way to Kashi or wherever else in North India.

00:26:31.240 --> 00:26:36.560
[Guest]: The sea made access to other countries easier than it did to other parts of the Indian subcontinent.

00:26:36.560 --> 00:26:39.560
[Guest]: So that is why Kerala evolved its own culture.

00:26:39.560 --> 00:26:43.160
[Guest]: The funny thing is, despite exposure with all these foreigners, it retained many of

00:26:43.160 --> 00:26:45.080
[Guest]: its original tribalistic elements also.

00:26:45.080 --> 00:26:49.520
[Guest]: A lot of tribal gods have survived, our Kava culture, the groves have survived with what

00:26:49.520 --> 00:26:52.840
[Guest]: are essentially pre-Brahmin, pre-Sanskritic gods.

00:26:52.840 --> 00:26:54.240
[Guest]: The matrilineal system survived.

00:26:54.240 --> 00:26:58.800
[Guest]: For some reason, despite all this exposure to patriarchal families and patriarchal religions

00:26:58.800 --> 00:27:03.120
[Guest]: and travelers and traders, matrilinealism stuck very strong in the royal families in

00:27:03.120 --> 00:27:08.040
[Guest]: the landed communities of Kerala and even in some very prominent lower caste groups.

00:27:08.040 --> 00:27:11.480
[Guest]: So you know, Kerala retained some sense of its independent identity.

00:27:11.480 --> 00:27:16.200
[Guest]: It retained a certain, you know, image of itself, all the same, constantly interacting

00:27:16.200 --> 00:27:17.200
[Guest]: with the world.

00:27:17.200 --> 00:27:18.200
[Guest]: For me, it's a great example.

00:27:18.200 --> 00:27:20.880
[Guest]: For example, right now, we're thinking about Indianness, right?

00:27:20.880 --> 00:27:24.520
[Guest]: There are ways to retain your Hinduness, there are ways to retain your Sanskriticness, there's

00:27:24.520 --> 00:27:28.360
[Guest]: ways to retain your Indianness, as it were, within whatever cultural parameters you're

00:27:28.360 --> 00:27:32.280
[Guest]: comfortable with, but also to engage with the world without feeling like it's some kind

00:27:32.280 --> 00:27:36.440
[Guest]: of threat, without feeling that foreign ideas and foreigners and anything that comes from

00:27:36.440 --> 00:27:37.880
[Guest]: outside is a bad thing.

00:27:37.880 --> 00:27:38.880
[Guest]: You can do both.

00:27:38.880 --> 00:27:42.840
[Guest]: It's not an either or, you know, our history is full of the and factor.

00:27:42.840 --> 00:27:43.840
[Guest]: It's both.

00:27:43.840 --> 00:27:44.840
[Amit Varma]: You don't need to choose.

00:27:44.840 --> 00:27:49.160
[Amit Varma]: In fact, I had a great episode a year and a half back with Vikram Doctor on Indian food,

00:27:49.160 --> 00:27:53.240
[Amit Varma]: which is basically about how all Indian food essentially came from outside.

00:27:53.240 --> 00:27:56.400
[Amit Varma]: There's very little that is originally Indian and yet all of it is Indian.

00:27:56.400 --> 00:27:57.400
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, sure.

00:27:57.400 --> 00:27:59.240
[Amit Varma]: It came from outside, but we made it our own.

00:27:59.240 --> 00:28:02.360
[Amit Varma]: And a couple of thoughts strike me from what you just said.

00:28:02.360 --> 00:28:08.240
[Amit Varma]: One is the mistake I often make and I caution others against making is thinking of India

00:28:08.240 --> 00:28:13.120
[Amit Varma]: as that mental, you know, you have that mental map in your head that, oh, this is India.

00:28:13.120 --> 00:28:17.000
[Amit Varma]: And there in the south, there's Tamil Nadu, Kerala, and these are all parts of this whole.

00:28:17.000 --> 00:28:21.660
[Amit Varma]: But as you point out, you know, this mental map is a relatively recent construction.

00:28:21.660 --> 00:28:25.560
[Amit Varma]: You actually have a Kerala if you look at it geographically, which is separated from

00:28:25.560 --> 00:28:27.080
[Amit Varma]: the rest of what we now call India.

00:28:27.080 --> 00:28:32.400
[Amit Varma]: And as you point out, it's more plausible for a lot of trade to happen over the seas

00:28:32.400 --> 00:28:35.720
[Amit Varma]: than say for a Kerala Hindu to go to Kashi.

00:28:35.720 --> 00:28:41.560
[Amit Varma]: The other important thing that this syncreticness of Kerala illustrates to me is the value of

00:28:41.560 --> 00:28:46.360
[Amit Varma]: globalization and free markets that they lead to an open society necessarily.

00:28:46.360 --> 00:28:50.720
[Amit Varma]: Because you know, if you are trading in a free market, it is in your interest to trade

00:28:50.720 --> 00:28:55.400
[Amit Varma]: with as wide an economic network as you can, you will discriminate less, which is not to

00:28:55.400 --> 00:28:59.360
[Amit Varma]: say not at all, but you will discriminate less, you will be more open.

00:28:59.360 --> 00:29:03.960
[Amit Varma]: And you know, that's the key to an open society, you cannot have an open society without also

00:29:03.960 --> 00:29:07.600
[Amit Varma]: having open trade and free markets.

00:29:07.600 --> 00:29:11.200
[Amit Varma]: But it's interesting that despite all of this, another thing that comes through very strongly

00:29:11.200 --> 00:29:16.600
[Amit Varma]: in your writing and in the ivory throne, is that despite this openness and this globalization

00:29:16.600 --> 00:29:21.520
[Amit Varma]: and all of the and even the matrilineal nature of society, which we'll discuss after this,

00:29:21.520 --> 00:29:27.120
[Amit Varma]: there are these very stark divisions, which are most clearly exemplified in the solidity

00:29:27.120 --> 00:29:31.840
[Amit Varma]: and the rigidity of the caste system, which is perhaps in many ways worse in Kerala than

00:29:31.840 --> 00:29:33.240
[Amit Varma]: other parts of India.

00:29:33.240 --> 00:29:34.240
[Amit Varma]: What explains that contradiction?

00:29:34.240 --> 00:29:35.240
[Amit Varma]: Tell me a bit about it.

00:29:35.240 --> 00:29:40.200
[Guest]: You know, Kerala was called famously the lunatic asylum of India by Swami Vivekananda, he knew

00:29:40.200 --> 00:29:42.080
[Guest]: caste, he had seen the caste system.

00:29:42.080 --> 00:29:45.160
[Guest]: And then he came to Kerala where he saw not only untouchability, but also things like

00:29:45.160 --> 00:29:46.160
[Guest]: unapproachability.

00:29:46.160 --> 00:29:50.200
[Guest]: There are distances certain castes had to keep from other castes, which are superior

00:29:50.200 --> 00:29:54.040
[Guest]: castes, because even their shadow, even their breath, even passing nearby could pollute

00:29:54.040 --> 00:29:55.040
[Amit Varma]: these.

00:29:55.040 --> 00:29:59.160
[Amit Varma]: I think you pointed out some castes cannot get within 90 meters of a Brahmin and 50 meters

00:29:59.160 --> 00:30:00.160
[Guest]: of a Nair.

00:30:00.160 --> 00:30:03.600
[Guest]: Yeah, there are there are rules like that about all of these things.

00:30:03.600 --> 00:30:07.080
[Guest]: There's even in some parts of Kerala, I think in my, where my family comes from, this caste

00:30:07.080 --> 00:30:08.080
[Guest]: doesn't exist.

00:30:08.080 --> 00:30:11.080
[Guest]: But there is a caste that was only allowed to come out at night, they're not allowed

00:30:11.080 --> 00:30:14.600
[Guest]: to see daylight and be seen by other people during the daylight, because even seeing them

00:30:14.600 --> 00:30:17.200
[Guest]: no matter what distance can can pollute you.

00:30:17.200 --> 00:30:21.760
[Guest]: So there's this kind of chaos and you know, madness also in Kerala society.

00:30:21.760 --> 00:30:25.800
[Guest]: You find this in some ways, I think part of it is also because of waves of immigration.

00:30:25.800 --> 00:30:29.760
[Guest]: Now, Kerala legend from the beginning says that Kerala is a country of immigrants.

00:30:29.760 --> 00:30:33.440
[Guest]: So the story is Parashuram brought all the Brahmins here and gave this land to the Brahmins.

00:30:33.440 --> 00:30:37.680
[Guest]: But at first the Brahmins had to discover that the land was completely occupied by ferocious

00:30:37.680 --> 00:30:38.680
[Guest]: Nagas.

00:30:38.680 --> 00:30:41.640
[Guest]: Now you can read that as serpents or you can read that as local tribes.

00:30:41.640 --> 00:30:45.440
[Guest]: And these Nagas would then push these Brahmins out, the Brahmins had to come back again and

00:30:45.440 --> 00:30:50.760
[Guest]: then make peace with the Nagas, except and why is it that all Kerala houses have grooves

00:30:50.760 --> 00:30:55.080
[Guest]: like in the house, one corner will be set apart in the compound as a groove, where it's

00:30:55.080 --> 00:30:58.840
[Guest]: allowed to run wild and anything is allowed to grow and there'll be a Naga statue in that.

00:30:58.840 --> 00:31:02.880
[Guest]: It's some kind of an old God that existed and the Brahmins basically accepted that God.

00:31:02.880 --> 00:31:08.080
[Guest]: So as the waves of immigrants come in, you find an increasing amount of temple construction.

00:31:08.080 --> 00:31:12.680
[Guest]: That's how a region that was largely forests and not agrarian yet becomes increasingly

00:31:12.680 --> 00:31:14.120
[Guest]: an agrarian society.

00:31:14.120 --> 00:31:18.280
[Guest]: That agrarian system seems to have been led by a lot of these upper castes, which is basically

00:31:18.280 --> 00:31:22.520
[Guest]: the Brahmins and the Nagas and those who tilted towards the future upper castes.

00:31:22.520 --> 00:31:26.520
[Guest]: Agrarian society meant wealth, wealth meant cornering resources and becoming more powerful,

00:31:26.520 --> 00:31:30.200
[Guest]: which meant that people who originally lived there, which is the later Dalit castes of

00:31:30.200 --> 00:31:34.280
[Guest]: Kerala, the Kauravas, the Pulayas, the Pulayas were an aggressive slave caste.

00:31:34.280 --> 00:31:38.360
[Guest]: But if you talk to them, the older members of the community, this is not written down

00:31:38.360 --> 00:31:42.080
[Guest]: anywhere, but they have their legends of Pulaya kings, of Pulaya chieftains, of people who

00:31:42.080 --> 00:31:44.680
[Guest]: had forts and so on in their community.

00:31:44.680 --> 00:31:48.760
[Guest]: But these were all, I think, forest communities at some point and they were slowly enslaved

00:31:48.760 --> 00:31:53.200
[Guest]: as urbanization and agrarianism built up, thanks to the immigrant communities that came

00:31:53.200 --> 00:31:55.240
[Guest]: in over different periods of time.

00:31:55.240 --> 00:31:56.600
[Guest]: That's how the caste system picks up.

00:31:56.600 --> 00:31:59.640
[Guest]: It's different groups that arrived at different times, sort of putting them into different

00:31:59.640 --> 00:32:00.640
[Guest]: boxes.

00:32:00.640 --> 00:32:04.240
[Guest]: But all the same, the upper castes had a lot to gel with.

00:32:04.240 --> 00:32:08.560
[Guest]: For example, in a Brahmin family, only if there are three sons, only the eldest is allowed

00:32:08.560 --> 00:32:12.760
[Guest]: to marry a Brahmin woman, because that way you only have one line in which succession

00:32:12.760 --> 00:32:16.200
[Guest]: happens in the Brahmin community, which means your property stays intact.

00:32:16.200 --> 00:32:17.200
[Guest]: It doesn't get partitioned.

00:32:17.200 --> 00:32:20.720
[Guest]: So if all three brothers marry Brahmin women and have Brahmin kids, there are three heirs,

00:32:20.720 --> 00:32:22.280
[Guest]: you have to split the property.

00:32:22.280 --> 00:32:25.960
[Guest]: So if only the eldest produces a Brahmin heir, the other two brothers marry non-Brahmin

00:32:25.960 --> 00:32:26.960
[Guest]: women.

00:32:26.960 --> 00:32:30.540
[Guest]: So they go and marry these matrilineal women from matrilineal communities.

00:32:30.540 --> 00:32:34.040
[Guest]: So that may be a Kshatriya princess or it may be a Shudra Naya.

00:32:34.040 --> 00:32:38.840
[Guest]: Now remember, Shudra does not mean low caste in the sense, Shudra still Sa Varna, which

00:32:38.840 --> 00:32:40.560
[Guest]: is in the Varna system.

00:32:40.560 --> 00:32:44.720
[Guest]: So Brahmins in Kerala said it was Brahmins, a few upgraded Nayas who wore the sacred thread

00:32:44.720 --> 00:32:48.120
[Guest]: as officially Kshatriyas, and then everyone else is a Shudra.

00:32:48.120 --> 00:32:50.560
[Guest]: But the Shudras were powerful landed communities.

00:32:50.560 --> 00:32:54.400
[Guest]: So they would marry the Shudra women also, with the result that in the next generation,

00:32:54.400 --> 00:32:58.320
[Guest]: you may have one son who's the Brahmin, say the temple priest, the second cousin would

00:32:58.320 --> 00:33:02.640
[Guest]: have married would it would be the son of this princess or whatever, and the local Raja.

00:33:02.640 --> 00:33:06.760
[Guest]: The third brother's son would be the local warlord or Naya chieftain or Naya general

00:33:06.760 --> 00:33:07.760
[Guest]: or whatever.

00:33:07.760 --> 00:33:09.960
[Guest]: So all three are cousins, they belong to different castes.

00:33:09.960 --> 00:33:12.520
[Guest]: One is a Brahmin, one is a Kshatriya, one is the warrior.

00:33:12.520 --> 00:33:17.000
[Guest]: And they therefore ensure that that upper caste prerogative and power they have is preserved.

00:33:17.000 --> 00:33:21.240
[Guest]: So the caste system was extremely brutal to those who are Avarna, out of that system.

00:33:21.240 --> 00:33:24.800
[Guest]: But the Savarnas made sure they were constantly gelling with each other through intermarriage

00:33:24.800 --> 00:33:29.040
[Guest]: and through links of not only economic exchange, but also the exchange of blood.

00:33:29.040 --> 00:33:33.440
[Amit Varma]: In fact, there's an amusing chapter in the ivory throne about how you mentioned, you

00:33:33.440 --> 00:33:37.440
[Amit Varma]: know, upgraded Naya is about how Martandu Varma who sort of resurrected the house of

00:33:37.440 --> 00:33:42.720
[Amit Varma]: Travancore as it were, was an upgraded Naya, for respectability, they did various rituals

00:33:42.720 --> 00:33:43.720
[Amit Varma]: and all that.

00:33:43.720 --> 00:33:44.720
[Guest]: So he could call himself a Kshatriya.

00:33:44.720 --> 00:33:48.920
[Guest]: And it's not just him, a lot of, and the funniest is there are, there are families that got

00:33:48.920 --> 00:33:52.640
[Guest]: stuck midway, like they were in the process of upgrading and then colonialism hits and

00:33:52.640 --> 00:33:54.880
[Guest]: they never quite complete the process.

00:33:54.880 --> 00:33:58.680
[Guest]: So usually people think that anybody in Kerala with the surname Varma, you know, your surname

00:33:58.680 --> 00:34:02.400
[Guest]: really is a Kshatriya, like who belongs to one of these palace communities.

00:34:02.400 --> 00:34:03.680
[Guest]: But there's a gradation within that.

00:34:03.680 --> 00:34:07.000
[Guest]: So you have at the beginning, the highest Kshatriya in Kerala is the Cochin Raja because

00:34:07.000 --> 00:34:08.400
[Guest]: his sacred thread is the oldest.

00:34:08.400 --> 00:34:12.280
[Guest]: In fact, there's this funny story where Martandu Varma has defeated the Cochin Raja and they've

00:34:12.280 --> 00:34:16.320
[Guest]: signed a treaty and they, you know, after they've done everything and they go and take

00:34:16.320 --> 00:34:20.240
[Guest]: a dip in the pond because in those days, that's a cultural thing, you go and bathe together.

00:34:20.240 --> 00:34:23.840
[Guest]: So then they take a dip in the pond and this Martandu Varma looks at the Cochin Raja's

00:34:23.840 --> 00:34:27.040
[Guest]: sacred thread and says, it's really filthy, it's all like turned black with dirt.

00:34:27.040 --> 00:34:30.440
[Guest]: And he says, you know, can't you clean this, look at mine, it's so pristine and white and

00:34:30.440 --> 00:34:31.440
[Guest]: so on.

00:34:31.440 --> 00:34:34.680
[Guest]: And the Cochin Raja says, you know, my Poonoola, my sacred thread is a little old as opposed

00:34:34.680 --> 00:34:36.120
[Guest]: to yours, which is new.

00:34:36.120 --> 00:34:39.640
[Guest]: The idea being that Martandu Varma is just a recent upgrade into the Kshatriya community,

00:34:39.640 --> 00:34:43.240
[Guest]: whereas the Cochin Raja has been there for so long that even his sacred thread has turned

00:34:43.240 --> 00:34:44.240
[Guest]: dirty.

00:34:44.240 --> 00:34:45.240
[Guest]: So there are families like the Cochin Raja.

00:34:45.240 --> 00:34:48.640
[Guest]: Then there are later people, for example, the Travenco family and its networks, which

00:34:48.640 --> 00:34:52.280
[Guest]: managed to gain the upgrade in the 17th century and the 18th century.

00:34:52.280 --> 00:34:55.320
[Guest]: Then there's another family called the Thekumkur and Vadkumkur Varmas.

00:34:55.320 --> 00:34:58.000
[Guest]: They have the surname of Varma, but they don't have the sacred thread.

00:34:58.000 --> 00:35:01.080
[Guest]: So they've literally been stuck in limbo where they're technically still Nayas, but they've

00:35:01.080 --> 00:35:03.400
[Guest]: managed to get the surname of the Kshatriyas.

00:35:03.400 --> 00:35:05.880
[Guest]: Then there are lower people like the caste of the Zamorin of Calicut.

00:35:05.880 --> 00:35:08.720
[Guest]: The Zamorins never thought it was worthwhile to go through this process.

00:35:08.720 --> 00:35:11.960
[Guest]: Everyone tried and decided it was too expensive to try and get the sacred thread.

00:35:11.960 --> 00:35:15.800
[Guest]: So they're stuck in another subgroup called Samantas, which are also neither Nayas fully

00:35:15.800 --> 00:35:18.400
[Guest]: nor fully Kshatriyas, somewhere stuck in the middle.

00:35:18.400 --> 00:35:23.160
[Guest]: So this process is fascinating because there are families you can specifically identify

00:35:23.160 --> 00:35:26.600
[Guest]: that tried to upgrade themselves within the last three, three and a half centuries and

00:35:26.600 --> 00:35:28.920
[Guest]: got stuck at different positions in the caste system.

00:35:28.920 --> 00:35:31.600
[Guest]: The British come and after that, there's no moving up or down.

00:35:31.600 --> 00:35:35.400
[Guest]: Then you're stuck because the British are cataloging everything and creating manuals

00:35:35.400 --> 00:35:36.400
[Guest]: and so on.

00:35:36.400 --> 00:35:39.840
[Guest]: So whatever box you were found in, in the 18th century became your final box.

00:35:39.840 --> 00:35:43.200
[Amit Varma]: And the British, of course, are very good at putting you in these boxes for their own

00:35:43.200 --> 00:35:46.680
[Unknown]: reasons of classification because they're trying to figure everything out.

00:35:46.680 --> 00:35:50.760
[Amit Varma]: And then those boxes will put you in become the fixed narrative and like we've discussed

00:35:50.760 --> 00:35:51.760
[Guest]: this in the past.

00:35:51.760 --> 00:35:52.760
[Guest]: There is no way to generalize.

00:35:52.760 --> 00:35:56.320
[Guest]: For example, you know, you find that a lot of this privilege comes from who can sit and

00:35:56.320 --> 00:35:57.680
[Guest]: eat with a Brahmin, for example.

00:35:57.680 --> 00:36:00.120
[Guest]: Now Nambudwari Brahmins in Kerala are extremely orthodox.

00:36:00.120 --> 00:36:03.960
[Guest]: Now the Zamorin of Calicut does not have a sacred thread.

00:36:03.960 --> 00:36:08.000
[Guest]: He's not technically a full Kshatriya, but he has the privilege of eating with Nambudwari.

00:36:08.000 --> 00:36:11.360
[Guest]: Nayas in general cannot cook for Nambudwari or feed them or sit and eat with them.

00:36:11.360 --> 00:36:14.740
[Guest]: But one particular Naya family, the Kavalapara Mupil Nayar, he has the privilege of eating

00:36:14.740 --> 00:36:15.740
[Guest]: with Brahmins.

00:36:15.740 --> 00:36:19.160
[Guest]: Now within this there are ranges, a Punul or a sacred thread wearing Kshatriya can sit

00:36:19.160 --> 00:36:21.600
[Guest]: next to a Brahmin and eat in the same line.

00:36:21.600 --> 00:36:24.040
[Guest]: Someone like the Zamorin can't do what is called Panti Bhojanam.

00:36:24.040 --> 00:36:25.040
[Guest]: He can do Sakshi Bhojanam.

00:36:25.040 --> 00:36:28.700
[Guest]: Sakshi Bhojanam is to sit in the same room, but not in the same line.

00:36:28.700 --> 00:36:32.680
[Guest]: The caste system is so intricate, you know, there are people who can sit with, there are

00:36:32.680 --> 00:36:35.560
[Guest]: people who can sit in the same room, there are people who can sit outside, there are

00:36:35.560 --> 00:36:37.480
[Guest]: people who are not even allowed on the threshold.

00:36:37.480 --> 00:36:40.080
[Guest]: My great-grandfather was a school headmaster.

00:36:40.080 --> 00:36:43.040
[Guest]: He had these aggressive laborers who belonged to Dalit communities.

00:36:43.040 --> 00:36:46.360
[Guest]: They were not allowed to look at the house, but because of Kerala's educational system

00:36:46.360 --> 00:36:50.840
[Guest]: which had built up from the 19th century, there were Puleya Dalit teachers in his school

00:36:50.840 --> 00:36:55.360
[Guest]: and every year as the headmaster, he gave a grand feast for people in our house.

00:36:55.360 --> 00:36:59.480
[Guest]: And it's fascinating to hear from my grandmother that even in the 40s, the rule was very simple.

00:36:59.480 --> 00:37:03.360
[Guest]: All the Nayas could sit in the veranda outside the kitchen area and they would be served

00:37:03.360 --> 00:37:04.960
[Guest]: their food there on leaves.

00:37:04.960 --> 00:37:09.280
[Guest]: The Christians etc. sat at a lower level because they were not allowed to sit inside the house.

00:37:09.280 --> 00:37:12.800
[Guest]: So they sat at a lower level on one of the steps and that's where they would eat.

00:37:12.800 --> 00:37:16.840
[Guest]: And the Puleya Dalit teachers, they would be served their food near the house, which

00:37:16.840 --> 00:37:20.200
[Guest]: the laborers were not allowed near the house, but because they were teachers they were allowed

00:37:20.200 --> 00:37:22.640
[Guest]: near the house, but their food was served in the cow shed.

00:37:22.640 --> 00:37:28.360
[Guest]: So the feast is happening in different spaces because each space has a caste-related connotation.

00:37:28.360 --> 00:37:32.320
[Guest]: It becomes extremely intricate and extremely complicated in Kerala.

00:37:32.320 --> 00:37:35.200
[Guest]: And that, you know, that it also reveals a lot about the caste system.

00:37:35.200 --> 00:37:38.440
[Guest]: The received wisdom we have that the caste system was Brahmin, Kshatriya, Vaishya, Shudra

00:37:38.440 --> 00:37:40.120
[Guest]: and these were the four castes etc.

00:37:40.120 --> 00:37:42.400
[Guest]: There was no such pan-Indian caste system.

00:37:42.400 --> 00:37:45.640
[Guest]: Every region, every place, it had its own Jati system.

00:37:45.640 --> 00:37:50.880
[Guest]: The Varna system was just a theoretical construct and it was also an instrument of manipulation.

00:37:50.880 --> 00:37:55.120
[Guest]: You could bribe Rajas to support various causes by promising them a higher Varna.

00:37:55.120 --> 00:37:58.360
[Guest]: And you know, that was it till the British came and looked up these texts and thought

00:37:58.360 --> 00:38:00.160
[Guest]: the texts held reality.

00:38:00.160 --> 00:38:04.160
[Guest]: These were not considered real categories, you know, for people in their everyday lived

00:38:04.160 --> 00:38:05.160
[Guest]: lives.

00:38:05.160 --> 00:38:07.160
[Guest]: Their everyday lived lives are much more complex.

00:38:07.160 --> 00:38:11.880
[Amit Varma]: And I guess one could say that your location in the caste system could be gauged by your

00:38:11.880 --> 00:38:14.040
[Amit Varma]: location while at mealtimes.

00:38:14.040 --> 00:38:17.880
[Amit Varma]: Is this stuff that you kind of discovered with this granularity while you were doing

00:38:17.880 --> 00:38:18.880
[Amit Varma]: research for your book?

00:38:18.880 --> 00:38:20.600
[Amit Varma]: Or is it something that filtered down to you anyway?

00:38:20.600 --> 00:38:21.600
[Guest]: I mean,

00:38:21.600 --> 00:38:25.360
[Guest]: I was in the course of the book because, you know, once although the book is primarily

00:38:25.360 --> 00:38:30.560
[Guest]: about this wonderful feuding, like these feuding sisters of Travancore, these royal women and

00:38:30.560 --> 00:38:34.160
[Guest]: that court intrigue and the Darbar politics and all of that and the British and how they

00:38:34.160 --> 00:38:35.720
[Guest]: intervene in all this.

00:38:35.720 --> 00:38:39.400
[Guest]: In the process, because Sethu Rashmi Bai also ruled, there's policy, there's decisions on

00:38:39.400 --> 00:38:40.800
[Guest]: social reform.

00:38:40.800 --> 00:38:44.600
[Guest]: Looking up these is what led me into these aspects and I found that it was fascinating.

00:38:44.600 --> 00:38:48.520
[Guest]: That's why the book took me six years because I wanted to not only weave in the palace gossip

00:38:48.520 --> 00:38:52.760
[Guest]: and all that was happening in a dramatic sense in the palace, but also these larger dynamics

00:38:52.760 --> 00:38:54.360
[Guest]: of a changing world.

00:38:54.360 --> 00:38:58.780
[Guest]: Because once colonialism came in and independence is approaching, that period is extremely fascinating

00:38:58.780 --> 00:39:03.480
[Guest]: between where colonialism is slowly starting to recede and fade and Indian nationalism

00:39:03.480 --> 00:39:04.480
[Guest]: is growing.

00:39:04.480 --> 00:39:07.880
[Guest]: How are royal families, you know, placed at that time in a very complicated position where

00:39:07.880 --> 00:39:10.340
[Guest]: they're not sure which way the future is turning.

00:39:10.340 --> 00:39:14.240
[Guest]: So at that time to study things with this greater granularity was, I thought, a very

00:39:14.240 --> 00:39:16.440
[Guest]: interesting, you know, prospect.

00:39:16.440 --> 00:39:21.360
[Amit Varma]: And what you do very well in your book is that you set up the narrative by talking about

00:39:21.360 --> 00:39:26.360
[Amit Varma]: all the tumult in the region we now called Kerala, but, you know, there's Calicut and

00:39:26.360 --> 00:39:31.360
[Amit Varma]: there's Cochin and there's Travancore and all that for maybe 300 years before the British

00:39:31.360 --> 00:39:35.600
[Amit Varma]: finally come, you know, from the time the Portuguese come to Calicut and they have an

00:39:35.600 --> 00:39:42.640
[Amit Varma]: awkward time getting through and then the subsequent battles, Martinda Verma, you know,

00:39:42.640 --> 00:39:48.040
[Amit Varma]: and more part of Verma's reviving the fate of Travancore and then colonialism coming

00:39:48.040 --> 00:39:52.400
[Amit Varma]: in and everything kind of settling down to this default thing where the British are now

00:39:52.400 --> 00:39:53.400
[Amit Varma]: in charge.

00:39:53.400 --> 00:39:55.400
[Amit Varma]: Just take me through a little bit of the tumult of that period.

00:39:55.400 --> 00:40:00.080
[Guest]: You know, it is a very bloody period in the sense that colonialism, so we were talking

00:40:00.080 --> 00:40:02.040
[Guest]: about the Arab traders in Calicut and so on.

00:40:02.040 --> 00:40:04.860
[Guest]: They had a wonderful equation going on for a long time.

00:40:04.860 --> 00:40:08.800
[Guest]: Then you find that the Chinese withdraw from the international seas, which is a huge thing.

00:40:08.800 --> 00:40:10.240
[Guest]: It's not given its due.

00:40:10.240 --> 00:40:13.200
[Guest]: But if the Chinese had continued to be in the Arabian Sea, their ships were 10 times

00:40:13.200 --> 00:40:15.000
[Guest]: larger than these European ships.

00:40:15.000 --> 00:40:18.600
[Guest]: The Chinese had the capacity to kick Europeans back to Europe and, you know, retain control

00:40:18.600 --> 00:40:21.320
[Guest]: of the Arabian Sea and trade in general.

00:40:21.320 --> 00:40:24.680
[Amit Varma]: And were they interested in colonizing others like the Europeans were or were they just

00:40:24.680 --> 00:40:25.680
[Guest]: happy to trade?

00:40:25.680 --> 00:40:26.680
[Guest]: I think they were happy to trade.

00:40:26.680 --> 00:40:30.080
[Guest]: They had a few outposts here and there and they had a certain, let's say, network of

00:40:30.080 --> 00:40:31.080
[Amit Varma]: influence.

00:40:31.080 --> 00:40:32.960
[Amit Varma]: So the whole history of the subcontinent would have been very different.

00:40:32.960 --> 00:40:36.440
[Guest]: The Chinese had remained, but the Chinese became isolationist for some, their own internal

00:40:36.440 --> 00:40:37.440
[Guest]: reasons at that time.

00:40:37.440 --> 00:40:38.960
[Guest]: So the Chinese withdrew.

00:40:38.960 --> 00:40:41.480
[Guest]: So it was left, the seas were left only to the Arabs.

00:40:41.480 --> 00:40:44.680
[Guest]: Now you have the Europeans coming in with their new technologies and their new angst

00:40:44.680 --> 00:40:46.800
[Guest]: to sort of take charge of it.

00:40:46.800 --> 00:40:50.120
[Guest]: They try and come and negotiate with these land rulers in Kerala, but they find that

00:40:50.120 --> 00:40:51.840
[Guest]: they can't beat these rulers on land.

00:40:51.840 --> 00:40:53.200
[Guest]: And the rulers have a good deal with the Arabs.

00:40:53.200 --> 00:40:57.040
[Guest]: So why should they entertain these white men from what they think is a barbaric country?

00:40:57.040 --> 00:40:58.040
[Guest]: They thought the Portuguese were barbaric.

00:40:58.040 --> 00:40:59.360
[Guest]: You know, that's what the Zamorin thought.

00:40:59.360 --> 00:41:01.160
[Guest]: He thought of them as barbarians.

00:41:01.160 --> 00:41:03.840
[Guest]: It's only later that colonizers started calling Indians barbarians.

00:41:03.840 --> 00:41:05.680
[Guest]: First it was the other way around.

00:41:05.680 --> 00:41:08.480
[Guest]: Then these guys discover that they actually have more power at sea.

00:41:08.480 --> 00:41:10.360
[Guest]: The Portuguese and the Europeans in general.

00:41:10.360 --> 00:41:13.520
[Guest]: So they start, you know, essentially it's piracy and terrorism at sea.

00:41:13.520 --> 00:41:14.520
[Guest]: They start sinking ships.

00:41:14.520 --> 00:41:16.240
[Guest]: They start preventing trade from happening.

00:41:16.240 --> 00:41:20.880
[Guest]: They start playing party pooper till these Rajas are forced to come to the table.

00:41:20.880 --> 00:41:25.840
[Guest]: Now this unleashes a whole set of new dynamics because now what's happening is the old powers

00:41:25.840 --> 00:41:29.800
[Guest]: like the Zamorin and his networks with the Arabs, they start fading and these European

00:41:29.800 --> 00:41:30.800
[Guest]: companies come up.

00:41:30.800 --> 00:41:35.440
[Guest]: And the European companies have an active interest in promoting smaller, less ambitious

00:41:35.440 --> 00:41:40.200
[Guest]: rulers like the Zamorin, using them as puppets and building up their own profile in Kerala.

00:41:40.200 --> 00:41:41.560
[Guest]: That's where you find the Kochi Raja comes up.

00:41:41.560 --> 00:41:45.520
[Guest]: The Kochi Raja's career for the last five centuries has always been, has entirely been

00:41:45.520 --> 00:41:48.400
[Guest]: being the puppet in the hands of one European company or the other.

00:41:48.400 --> 00:41:52.000
[Guest]: The crown of Kochi, which is now kept in a palace in Tripunathara in a museum.

00:41:52.000 --> 00:41:54.800
[Guest]: If you look at the crown, there's the emblem of the Dutch East India Company on it because

00:41:54.800 --> 00:41:57.100
[Guest]: they made the crown and gave it to the Kochi Raja.

00:41:57.100 --> 00:42:01.920
[Guest]: Even his crown is inscribed with the company's logo and a logo because he's not entirely

00:42:01.920 --> 00:42:02.920
[Guest]: free.

00:42:02.920 --> 00:42:07.320
[Guest]: Now what happens in the south of Kerala, which is, you know, Travancore at that time is essentially

00:42:07.320 --> 00:42:08.320
[Guest]: a political backwater.

00:42:08.320 --> 00:42:11.280
[Guest]: It's a small sliver between Kanyakumari and Trivandrum.

00:42:11.280 --> 00:42:12.360
[Guest]: Nobody cares very much about it.

00:42:12.360 --> 00:42:14.200
[Guest]: The family is not even considered fully Malayali.

00:42:14.200 --> 00:42:16.480
[Guest]: They're very exposed to Tamil society.

00:42:16.480 --> 00:42:19.120
[Guest]: So they're not considered de facto shuddha Malayalis.

00:42:19.120 --> 00:42:23.680
[Guest]: Now this prince discovers that this chaos, to quote from a line from Game of Thrones,

00:42:23.680 --> 00:42:24.680
[Guest]: chaos is a ladder.

00:42:24.680 --> 00:42:26.880
[Guest]: You can use that to your own advantage.

00:42:26.880 --> 00:42:27.880
[Guest]: What does he do?

00:42:27.880 --> 00:42:30.480
[Guest]: He starts getting weapons from the East India Company.

00:42:30.480 --> 00:42:31.760
[Guest]: The English are still not a major factor.

00:42:31.760 --> 00:42:34.600
[Guest]: It's the Dutch by this time, we're talking about the 18th century.

00:42:34.600 --> 00:42:37.720
[Guest]: The Portuguese are displaced by the Dutch and now the Dutch are in control and the English

00:42:37.720 --> 00:42:39.800
[Guest]: are about to displace the Dutch.

00:42:39.800 --> 00:42:43.260
[Guest]: So Marthandu Varma acquires weapons, etc. from the English.

00:42:43.260 --> 00:42:48.680
[Guest]: He gets a prisoner of war from the Dutch to come and start training his armies in a modern

00:42:48.680 --> 00:42:49.740
[Guest]: Western style.

00:42:49.740 --> 00:42:53.640
[Guest]: He starts getting mercenaries from Tamil Nadu and does something unheard of in Kerala, which

00:42:53.640 --> 00:42:55.360
[Guest]: is to start conquering territory.

00:42:55.360 --> 00:42:58.440
[Guest]: Earlier when kings defeated other kings, they just made them vassals.

00:42:58.440 --> 00:42:59.440
[Guest]: They do not conquer.

00:42:59.440 --> 00:43:00.440
[Guest]: They do not annex territory.

00:43:00.440 --> 00:43:01.800
[Guest]: Very rarely did that happen.

00:43:01.800 --> 00:43:07.240
[Guest]: Marthandu makes this his chief political activity and he ends up conquering everything up to

00:43:07.240 --> 00:43:08.400
[Guest]: Cochin.

00:43:08.400 --> 00:43:11.520
[Guest]: But the timing is also important because suddenly communication is easier.

00:43:11.520 --> 00:43:15.480
[Guest]: The earlier hassles that existed, say in the 15th and 16th century, no longer apply in

00:43:15.480 --> 00:43:16.480
[Guest]: the 18th century.

00:43:16.480 --> 00:43:17.720
[Guest]: Things are moving much faster.

00:43:17.720 --> 00:43:19.400
[Guest]: The world is becoming a faster place.

00:43:19.400 --> 00:43:21.120
[Guest]: The English companies are facilitating that.

00:43:21.120 --> 00:43:22.960
[Guest]: New weapons and technologies are coming in.

00:43:22.960 --> 00:43:25.080
[Guest]: New forms of fortification are coming in.

00:43:25.080 --> 00:43:28.040
[Guest]: And he's reaching out to people beyond the Kerala ecosystem.

00:43:28.040 --> 00:43:31.480
[Guest]: He at one point reaches out to Hyder Ali asking for assistance.

00:43:31.480 --> 00:43:35.920
[Guest]: So you know, he builds up a new modern state in a modern changing universe.

00:43:35.920 --> 00:43:40.880
[Guest]: He uses the chaos that colonialism and early colonialism is unleashing in the Indian subcontinent

00:43:40.880 --> 00:43:44.440
[Guest]: and uses that to his advantage to create the state of Travancore.

00:43:44.440 --> 00:43:49.680
[Guest]: That is how he sort of, you know, turns a rather sad declining situation to his advantage,

00:43:49.680 --> 00:43:50.680
[Guest]: benefits from it.

00:43:50.680 --> 00:43:54.320
[Guest]: Now, the funny thing is he's also a Hindu king with aspirations of his own.

00:43:54.320 --> 00:43:59.040
[Guest]: So first he has to upgrade himself in caste because if you read Marthandavarma's story,

00:43:59.040 --> 00:44:01.640
[Guest]: what is fascinating is that he was still then first among equals.

00:44:01.640 --> 00:44:03.000
[Guest]: Royal blood was not sacred.

00:44:03.000 --> 00:44:05.760
[Guest]: His nobility was constantly trying to murder him when he was a prince because they don't

00:44:05.760 --> 00:44:07.160
[Guest]: like him.

00:44:07.160 --> 00:44:09.760
[Guest]: He decides, therefore, that royal blood must become more sacred.

00:44:09.760 --> 00:44:14.920
[Guest]: People must hesitate to drop or sort of stab royalty and, you know, spill their blood.

00:44:14.920 --> 00:44:18.320
[Guest]: So he decides that that means your caste has to be upgraded and a certain awe has to be

00:44:18.320 --> 00:44:19.320
[Guest]: built around royalty.

00:44:19.320 --> 00:44:20.320
[Guest]: All kings do it.

00:44:20.320 --> 00:44:21.320
[Guest]: The Delhi Sultans did it.

00:44:21.320 --> 00:44:26.200
[Guest]: They use protocol and state and court decorum and culture etc to make yourself look extremely

00:44:26.200 --> 00:44:31.000
[Guest]: powerful and extremely, let's say, otherworldly, superhuman in some ways.

00:44:31.000 --> 00:44:34.200
[Guest]: So Marthandavarma says I need a caste upgrade.

00:44:34.200 --> 00:44:35.200
[Guest]: He gets Brahmins.

00:44:35.200 --> 00:44:37.480
[Guest]: Now all the Nabudri Brahmins in Kerala are in northern Kerala.

00:44:37.480 --> 00:44:40.840
[Guest]: So he's not, they don't actually live here, but he has to find a way to woo them and give

00:44:40.840 --> 00:44:42.100
[Guest]: him a caste upgrade.

00:44:42.100 --> 00:44:46.280
[Guest]: The process is the ritual called Hiranyagarbha where they construct a cow made entirely out

00:44:46.280 --> 00:44:47.280
[Guest]: of gold.

00:44:47.280 --> 00:44:49.680
[Guest]: The king goes in through the cow, sits inside the cow.

00:44:49.680 --> 00:44:51.360
[Guest]: They chant mantras of birth.

00:44:51.360 --> 00:44:54.160
[Guest]: So and then he emerges from under the tail of the cow and now he's reborn.

00:44:54.160 --> 00:44:57.560
[Guest]: He's now reborn as a Kshatriya who can wear the sacred thread, part of the Soma Vamsha

00:44:57.560 --> 00:45:00.600
[Guest]: or the house of the moon, etc, etc.

00:45:00.600 --> 00:45:03.040
[Guest]: So he gains, first of all, his caste upgrade.

00:45:03.040 --> 00:45:06.720
[Guest]: The other thing is once you've got a caste upgrade, you can now no longer let your Nayas

00:45:06.720 --> 00:45:09.700
[Guest]: who are technically Shudras, you know, they can't come and touch you and serve you.

00:45:09.700 --> 00:45:13.800
[Guest]: So you need Brahmins to come and surround you and sort of have this Brahminical decorous

00:45:13.800 --> 00:45:14.800
[Guest]: system around you.

00:45:14.800 --> 00:45:16.680
[Guest]: Now, as I said, all the Nabudris are in North Kerala.

00:45:16.680 --> 00:45:17.680
[Guest]: So what does he do?

00:45:17.680 --> 00:45:22.000
[Guest]: He imports Tamil Brahmins by the thousands into Kerala, gives them various incentives

00:45:22.000 --> 00:45:27.200
[Guest]: to come to his state, which is free feeding houses, lots of privileges and benefits, etc.

00:45:27.200 --> 00:45:30.800
[Guest]: So the Tamil Brahmins come in and they start surrounding the royal family.

00:45:30.800 --> 00:45:35.000
[Guest]: And then he creates a protocol around the royal family, which is even the language used

00:45:35.000 --> 00:45:36.960
[Guest]: for royalty has to be highly artificial.

00:45:36.960 --> 00:45:39.920
[Guest]: It's essentially like public relations now.

00:45:39.920 --> 00:45:43.180
[Guest]: Politicians know that on the one hand, they have to be in touch with the masses, etc.

00:45:43.180 --> 00:45:47.240
[Guest]: But the masses must never think of them as ordinary because familiarity breeds content.

00:45:47.240 --> 00:45:50.880
[Guest]: So Marthandwarman knows this rule and he's doing this in an 18th century format, which

00:45:50.880 --> 00:45:54.040
[Guest]: is that, you know, even as I said, language is artificial.

00:45:54.040 --> 00:45:57.360
[Guest]: So when a normal Malayali like myself, when I wake up in the morning, the first thing

00:45:57.360 --> 00:46:00.120
[Guest]: we do is palli dekha, which is to brush your teeth.

00:46:00.120 --> 00:46:03.320
[Guest]: For royalty, the word is tirumutta vilakka, the cleaning of the royal pearls, because

00:46:03.320 --> 00:46:05.560
[Guest]: royalty doesn't have teeth, it has pearls.

00:46:05.560 --> 00:46:09.760
[Guest]: You know, when a Raja or a Rani goes for a bath, it is not called a kuli, which is what

00:46:09.760 --> 00:46:11.600
[Guest]: we would use as a regular Malayali.

00:46:11.600 --> 00:46:12.600
[Guest]: That would be the word.

00:46:12.600 --> 00:46:15.440
[Guest]: They go for a palli nirata, the royal frolic in water.

00:46:15.440 --> 00:46:19.520
[Guest]: When they eat, it's called amrutheta, which is eating amruth or nectar, you're not eating

00:46:19.520 --> 00:46:20.960
[Guest]: normal food.

00:46:20.960 --> 00:46:26.720
[Guest]: When they cry, it's called trikandnirvarkuva, you know, the royal like water is emerging

00:46:26.720 --> 00:46:28.520
[Guest]: from its eyes and things like that.

00:46:28.520 --> 00:46:31.840
[Guest]: Then when the Queen of Travancore gets pregnant, you know, the proclamation is never she's

00:46:31.840 --> 00:46:32.840
[Guest]: pregnant.

00:46:32.840 --> 00:46:35.080
[Guest]: Pregnancy is not a word you use for Queens and royalty.

00:46:35.080 --> 00:46:38.000
[Guest]: The word is tiruvairvanu, the royal womb is occupied.

00:46:38.000 --> 00:46:41.640
[Guest]: And then when the Queen delivers the baby, it's tiruvairvazhinu, the royal womb is vacated

00:46:41.640 --> 00:46:45.620
[Guest]: because Queens don't do such human things as give birth and get pregnant.

00:46:45.620 --> 00:46:49.840
[Guest]: And when a Maharaja of Travancore is on his deathbed, they find a Tamil Brahmin and they

00:46:49.840 --> 00:46:52.240
[Guest]: get the Tamil Brahmin to embrace the dying Raja.

00:46:52.240 --> 00:46:53.240
[Guest]: What is he doing?

00:46:53.240 --> 00:46:54.760
[Guest]: He's handing over his sins to the Brahmin.

00:46:54.760 --> 00:46:59.000
[Guest]: So he can get moksha and go straight to, you know, whatever, heaven or whatever.

00:46:59.000 --> 00:47:02.520
[Guest]: And the Brahmin is paid 10,000 rupees taken to the border of Travancore and unceremoniously

00:47:02.520 --> 00:47:05.920
[Guest]: kicked out to disappear with the sins forever.

00:47:05.920 --> 00:47:07.960
[Guest]: And when the king dies, finally, it's called nadni.

00:47:07.960 --> 00:47:12.120
[Guest]: He's ended ruling his rule in this nada, this kingdom, he's now moved to the other kingdom,

00:47:12.120 --> 00:47:13.960
[Guest]: the heavenly kingdom to rule that.

00:47:13.960 --> 00:47:18.120
[Guest]: So even the language is highly artificial vocabularies constructed around the royal

00:47:18.120 --> 00:47:22.840
[Guest]: family to reinforce the idea that these people are so special, they're so wonderful, they're

00:47:22.840 --> 00:47:24.880
[Guest]: so not like you and me.

00:47:24.880 --> 00:47:27.840
[Guest]: That is to be constantly regenerated and constantly done.

00:47:27.840 --> 00:47:31.320
[Guest]: The irony is he ends up creating what, and Travancore consciously called itself a Hindu

00:47:31.320 --> 00:47:35.600
[Guest]: state in the 19th century, called itself the Hindu state of Travancore.

00:47:35.600 --> 00:47:39.240
[Guest]: But how is the Hindu state created with East India Company arms by a Dutch mercenary who

00:47:39.240 --> 00:47:45.160
[Guest]: trained its forces by Tamil mercenary armies and by a king who only after he did all this

00:47:45.160 --> 00:47:50.280
[Guest]: using all these instruments of modernity, he also used Brahminical culture to Sanskritize

00:47:50.280 --> 00:47:53.160
[Guest]: and to make himself the Sanskritic Indian king.

00:47:53.160 --> 00:47:56.840
[Guest]: But that Sanskritism was backed by forces that were unleashed by colonialism, just backed

00:47:56.840 --> 00:48:00.920
[Guest]: by forces that were entirely modern and vintage and not ancient by any stretch.

00:48:00.920 --> 00:48:01.920
[Amit Varma]: It's optics.

00:48:01.920 --> 00:48:03.520
[Guest]: It's really positioning.

00:48:03.520 --> 00:48:07.600
[Guest]: Using your ancient unbroken pure Kshatriya lineage was a very modern enterprise.

00:48:07.600 --> 00:48:08.600
[Amit Varma]: Right.

00:48:08.600 --> 00:48:09.600
[Amit Varma]: No.

00:48:09.600 --> 00:48:13.040
[Amit Varma]: And of course, you know, talking of these elaborate rituals and all that in your book,

00:48:13.040 --> 00:48:17.560
[Amit Varma]: there's a very long description and just reading it made me tired and want to dry myself with

00:48:17.560 --> 00:48:23.520
[Amit Varma]: towel of the young Sethu Lakshmibai, I think having a bath and the ritual it involved.

00:48:23.520 --> 00:48:25.040
[Amit Varma]: It is so incredibly elaborate.

00:48:25.040 --> 00:48:27.120
[Amit Varma]: I think everything would take two hours.

00:48:27.120 --> 00:48:28.120
[Amit Varma]: Yeah.

00:48:28.120 --> 00:48:31.520
[Amit Varma]: And what kind of strikes me also about Marthand Varma is that he's a very interesting character

00:48:31.520 --> 00:48:39.040
[Amit Varma]: in that he seems to combine a medieval brutality with an almost modern sense of real politic.

00:48:39.040 --> 00:48:42.320
[Amit Varma]: And so I'll just read out a couple of quotes from your book that give a sense of that because

00:48:42.320 --> 00:48:44.360
[Amit Varma]: I found this quite fascinating.

00:48:44.360 --> 00:48:48.880
[Amit Varma]: One is, of course, you know, your other books have tons of violence in them.

00:48:48.880 --> 00:48:55.040
[Amit Varma]: This one doesn't have so much, but still, this is this is a glimpse.

00:48:55.040 --> 00:49:00.840
[Amit Varma]: And what happens after he discovers a conspiracy in his court court soon enough and evidence

00:49:00.840 --> 00:49:03.960
[Amit Varma]: fell into the Raja's hands of a conspiracy at court.

00:49:03.960 --> 00:49:09.040
[Amit Varma]: He had the Pilamar arrested summarily and presented proof of their perfidy.

00:49:09.040 --> 00:49:14.040
[Amit Varma]: In what was unprecedented, instead of chastising the nobles by demoting their powers, but otherwise

00:49:14.040 --> 00:49:19.000
[Amit Varma]: leaving them unharmed, Marthand Varma ordered their immediate execution.

00:49:19.000 --> 00:49:23.600
[Amit Varma]: Their properties were attached and their women and children sold into slavery with not a

00:49:23.600 --> 00:49:30.340
[Amit Varma]: hint of mercy or sympathy and thus perished 42 noble houses of the realm, obliterating

00:49:30.340 --> 00:49:35.040
[Amit Varma]: internal opposition from the Raja's path and ringing the death knell of feudalism in the

00:49:35.040 --> 00:49:36.040
[Amit Varma]: region.

00:49:36.040 --> 00:49:39.000
[Amit Varma]: Stop, quote, very Game of Thrones style.

00:49:39.000 --> 00:49:42.800
[Amit Varma]: And the other quote is about when he's dying and you're right, quote, on his death bed

00:49:42.800 --> 00:49:48.120
[Amit Varma]: in 1758, he issued seven injunctions for political survival to his heirs.

00:49:48.120 --> 00:49:53.120
[Amit Varma]: The most crucial of which was that the friendship existing between the English East India Company

00:49:53.120 --> 00:49:58.120
[Amit Varma]: and Travancore should be maintained at any risk, and that full confidence should always

00:49:58.120 --> 00:50:02.880
[Amit Varma]: be placed in the support and aid of that honourable association.

00:50:02.880 --> 00:50:03.880
[Amit Varma]: Stop quote.

00:50:03.880 --> 00:50:07.960
[Amit Varma]: And there is a hint of practicality and like, I mean, I don't know whether it comes from

00:50:07.960 --> 00:50:12.880
[Amit Varma]: an understanding of what a force the East India Company can be or maybe it's just recognition

00:50:12.880 --> 00:50:18.760
[Amit Varma]: that his successors aren't as brilliant and enterprising as him, but it sets a tone for

00:50:18.760 --> 00:50:20.360
[Guest]: what is to happen in the centuries to come.

00:50:20.360 --> 00:50:23.400
[Guest]: It does, because without the British, the kingdom could not have survived.

00:50:23.400 --> 00:50:27.560
[Guest]: You know, the brutality, as you mentioned, is actually quite striking because there are

00:50:27.560 --> 00:50:29.400
[Guest]: still fisher families outside Trivandrum.

00:50:29.400 --> 00:50:34.600
[Guest]: There are villages where they're called fair fishermen, you know, villages, means fair.

00:50:34.600 --> 00:50:38.560
[Guest]: The idea being these people are descended from these upper caste Nair women who Marthandor

00:50:38.560 --> 00:50:39.560
[Guest]: sold into slavery.

00:50:39.560 --> 00:50:40.560
[Guest]: What did he do?

00:50:40.560 --> 00:50:41.560
[Guest]: Why is he doing that?

00:50:41.560 --> 00:50:44.920
[Guest]: Because by giving up these women and making them eat with and live with fishermen, you

00:50:44.920 --> 00:50:47.160
[Guest]: are forever reducing their caste position.

00:50:47.160 --> 00:50:49.160
[Guest]: They can never bounce back from something like that.

00:50:49.160 --> 00:50:52.920
[Guest]: Killing a family member, killing all the men, the women can still have babies in that family,

00:50:52.920 --> 00:50:54.600
[Guest]: the vamsha still survives.

00:50:54.600 --> 00:50:57.400
[Guest]: But you demote them in caste, you completely make them important.

00:50:57.400 --> 00:50:59.360
[Guest]: There's no way they can come back and harm you.

00:50:59.360 --> 00:51:00.720
[Guest]: There are so many stories.

00:51:00.720 --> 00:51:04.760
[Guest]: In fact, there's even a story, if you go to Trivandrum, next to the Padmanabhaswamy temple,

00:51:04.760 --> 00:51:06.360
[Guest]: there is this pond called the Padmateertham.

00:51:06.360 --> 00:51:09.520
[Guest]: It's a huge pond, massive tank really.

00:51:09.520 --> 00:51:11.920
[Guest]: The legend goes that it wasn't originally so big.

00:51:11.920 --> 00:51:15.520
[Guest]: Next to that, one of these courtiers had his huge mansion and the way Marthandor, once

00:51:15.520 --> 00:51:19.560
[Guest]: he defeats his various enemies, what he does is, it's called kolam thonduga in Malayalam.

00:51:19.560 --> 00:51:23.720
[Guest]: You not only destroy the house, you turn that spot into a pond and fill it with water so

00:51:23.720 --> 00:51:27.800
[Guest]: that any sign of a house having been there completely disappears from local and public

00:51:27.800 --> 00:51:28.800
[Guest]: memory.

00:51:28.800 --> 00:51:32.680
[Guest]: So get rid of the lineage, get rid of even the land and the property on which these people

00:51:32.680 --> 00:51:33.720
[Guest]: actually lived.

00:51:33.720 --> 00:51:37.560
[Guest]: And suddenly these people cease to exist, as far as the future is concerned.

00:51:37.560 --> 00:51:42.040
[Guest]: They no longer exist as even a concept for other rebels to rally around and sort of make

00:51:42.040 --> 00:51:46.260
[Guest]: them a focus for any kind of rebellion against the king.

00:51:46.260 --> 00:51:48.080
[Guest]: You see that even with politicians now.

00:51:48.080 --> 00:51:52.160
[Guest]: Why is it that the politicians always want to delegitimize somebody else?

00:51:52.160 --> 00:51:56.200
[Guest]: You delegitimize your rival because you have to make sure they become completely important.

00:51:56.200 --> 00:51:59.760
[Guest]: Nobody should be able to rally around them because they've been completely sort of stripped

00:51:59.760 --> 00:52:02.920
[Guest]: of any kind of legitimacy in the political system.

00:52:02.920 --> 00:52:06.440
[Guest]: And I guess painting them as anti-national is the easiest way to do that.

00:52:06.440 --> 00:52:09.880
[Guest]: You know, just now there's a politician who said, oh, maybe we should send the actual

00:52:09.880 --> 00:52:14.840
[Guest]: correct information on the CA to the Citizenship Amendment Act to Rahul Gandhi in Italian.

00:52:14.840 --> 00:52:18.440
[Guest]: All of this is suggesting that he's illegitimate, he doesn't belong here.

00:52:18.440 --> 00:52:22.640
[Guest]: It's trying to negate this person's right or even his claim to be here and saying that

00:52:22.640 --> 00:52:25.000
[Guest]: no, you are not a factor at all.

00:52:25.000 --> 00:52:28.920
[Guest]: And all of this is about the optics as much as it is about politics.

00:52:28.920 --> 00:52:34.400
[Amit Varma]: And interestingly, you'd imagine that, you know, one reads about Martanda Varma's brutality

00:52:34.400 --> 00:52:39.080
[Amit Varma]: and all of that, and you see all the violence raging and you think, oh, okay, it's a typical

00:52:39.080 --> 00:52:43.200
[Amit Varma]: patriarchal society, there must be toxic masculinity all over.

00:52:43.200 --> 00:52:49.200
[Amit Varma]: And yet, and yet, tell me a little bit about sort of the matrilineal nature of Kerala society

00:52:49.200 --> 00:52:53.440
[Amit Varma]: and how it sort of came to be and what form it took through these centuries.

00:52:53.440 --> 00:52:58.560
[Guest]: So the thing is, people often say matriarchal, it's not matriarchal, it's linear, matrilineal.

00:52:58.560 --> 00:53:03.240
[Guest]: Because at the end of the day, it's the men who actually hold a lot of power as well.

00:53:03.240 --> 00:53:05.880
[Guest]: It's not like the men are completely divested of influence.

00:53:05.880 --> 00:53:10.240
[Guest]: The only changes, to put it simplistically, the family is not man, wife and children.

00:53:10.240 --> 00:53:12.760
[Guest]: It is woman, her brother and her children.

00:53:12.760 --> 00:53:14.320
[Guest]: So the focus is the woman.

00:53:14.320 --> 00:53:15.320
[Guest]: The owner is the woman.

00:53:15.320 --> 00:53:19.680
[Guest]: So in the Zamorin of Calicut's family, the eldest female, even if she's a 12 year old

00:53:19.680 --> 00:53:24.480
[Guest]: girl, and the Zamorin himself is 70, and he's her grandfather, she's a granduncle of hers,

00:53:24.480 --> 00:53:29.040
[Guest]: he will still bow to her and call her Amma, which is mother, because a woman is the technical

00:53:29.040 --> 00:53:30.320
[Guest]: owner of the property.

00:53:30.320 --> 00:53:31.840
[Guest]: She is the head of the family.

00:53:31.840 --> 00:53:35.580
[Guest]: In Travancore similarly, the Raja's wife is only called Ammachi, Ammachi means mother

00:53:35.580 --> 00:53:36.880
[Guest]: of his highness's children.

00:53:36.880 --> 00:53:39.920
[Guest]: She is not queen, neither are his children royalty.

00:53:39.920 --> 00:53:42.480
[Guest]: They are normal, ordinary people.

00:53:42.480 --> 00:53:47.960
[Guest]: So for instance, one of the Maharajas of Travancore, let's say this one who died in 1924, his full

00:53:47.960 --> 00:53:52.360
[Guest]: title is His Highness Shri Padmanabha Dasa, Vanchipala, Shri Moolam Dhirnar, Damavarma

00:53:52.360 --> 00:53:57.320
[Guest]: Kulshekhara, Kiritapati, Manya Sultan, Maharaja Raja Ramaraja Bahadur, Shamsherjung.

00:53:57.320 --> 00:53:58.800
[Guest]: And then of course there are his English titles.

00:53:58.800 --> 00:54:01.760
[Guest]: But his son is simply Mr. Velayudhan Thambi.

00:54:01.760 --> 00:54:03.680
[Amit Varma]: And you can add a Shri, which is given to them.

00:54:03.680 --> 00:54:05.480
[Amit Varma]: Perhaps to his great relief.

00:54:05.480 --> 00:54:06.480
[Amit Varma]: That's all he is.

00:54:06.480 --> 00:54:08.600
[Guest]: Thambi, which is a surname, means brother.

00:54:08.600 --> 00:54:12.440
[Guest]: So you're saying this person is like a brother to the royal family, but he is not a Thamburan,

00:54:12.440 --> 00:54:14.240
[Guest]: which means he's not a royal himself.

00:54:14.240 --> 00:54:15.800
[Guest]: He's a relative of the royal family.

00:54:15.800 --> 00:54:16.960
[Guest]: So the king's son is a mister.

00:54:16.960 --> 00:54:17.960
[Guest]: The king has a string of titles.

00:54:17.960 --> 00:54:22.120
[Guest]: The king's son is always a mister and the king's wife is also a missus.

00:54:22.120 --> 00:54:25.520
[Guest]: So a Maharaja of Cochin, for example, had this very powerful wife.

00:54:25.520 --> 00:54:26.860
[Guest]: He died in 1932.

00:54:26.860 --> 00:54:28.280
[Guest]: The wife was never Maharani.

00:54:28.280 --> 00:54:30.600
[Guest]: She was always called, his name was Ramavarma.

00:54:30.600 --> 00:54:31.980
[Guest]: She was called Lady Ramavarma.

00:54:31.980 --> 00:54:34.480
[Guest]: She was never called Rani Parukutti Netiara, whatever her name was.

00:54:34.480 --> 00:54:36.180
[Guest]: She's called Lady Ramavarma.

00:54:36.180 --> 00:54:40.320
[Guest]: In his English title as Sir Ramavarma, his wife could be Lady Ramavarma.

00:54:40.320 --> 00:54:44.560
[Guest]: But in his family title of Raja, the Raniship went to his sister as per the matrilineal

00:54:44.560 --> 00:54:45.560
[Guest]: system.

00:54:45.560 --> 00:54:48.720
[Amit Varma]: And the sister's kids are the heirs.

00:54:48.720 --> 00:54:52.520
[Guest]: Heirs again, I mean, people often simplistically say it's the man's nephew who succeeds him.

00:54:52.520 --> 00:54:55.100
[Guest]: There is no such rule that says the nephew has to succeed him.

00:54:55.100 --> 00:54:59.320
[Guest]: The next oldest person in the matrilineal joint family is the ruler.

00:54:59.320 --> 00:55:04.840
[Guest]: That may be your brother, a nephew who's older than a brother, that nephew would rule first,

00:55:04.840 --> 00:55:07.200
[Guest]: even though he's technically a nephew in terms of relationship.

00:55:07.200 --> 00:55:11.120
[Guest]: If the nephew is somehow older, the nephew has the first claim to the throne, only then

00:55:11.120 --> 00:55:12.840
[Guest]: the other uncle who's younger.

00:55:12.840 --> 00:55:16.280
[Guest]: So age is the determining factor for both the male as well as the female.

00:55:16.280 --> 00:55:18.880
[Amit Varma]: This is possibly the origin of fudging birth certificates.

00:55:18.880 --> 00:55:22.200
[Amit Varma]: It did not happen in UP, Bihar sports teams.

00:55:22.200 --> 00:55:25.400
[Amit Varma]: Ah, you had to do it.

00:55:25.400 --> 00:55:28.120
[Guest]: So let's put it in the context of the Travancore royal family.

00:55:28.120 --> 00:55:31.480
[Guest]: The favorite analogy I give is through some of these court rituals.

00:55:31.480 --> 00:55:35.600
[Guest]: So the Maharani of Travancore, Setu Lakshmibai for example, she is the Maharani, her husband

00:55:35.600 --> 00:55:37.320
[Guest]: is only called the consort.

00:55:37.320 --> 00:55:38.640
[Guest]: He's not even usually called husband.

00:55:38.640 --> 00:55:40.160
[Guest]: He's just called the consort.

00:55:40.160 --> 00:55:44.800
[Guest]: The consort cannot sit in the presence of his wife unless she gives him permission.

00:55:44.800 --> 00:55:45.960
[Guest]: He can't call his wife by name.

00:55:45.960 --> 00:55:49.960
[Guest]: Till this husband of hers died in 1976, he always referred to his wife as her highness.

00:55:49.960 --> 00:55:51.960
[Guest]: He would ask his grandchildren, where is her highness?

00:55:51.960 --> 00:55:52.960
[Guest]: He'd never say, where's your grandmother?

00:55:52.960 --> 00:55:56.560
[Guest]: He'd say, where is her highness, because he was always aware that her position was superior

00:55:56.560 --> 00:55:57.560
[Guest]: to him.

00:55:57.560 --> 00:56:01.440
[Guest]: When they, you know, she was considered a great reformer because in the 1910s, she started

00:56:01.440 --> 00:56:03.720
[Guest]: traveling in the same car with her husband.

00:56:03.720 --> 00:56:04.880
[Guest]: Her uncle was scandalized.

00:56:04.880 --> 00:56:07.360
[Guest]: He said, he may be your husband, but he's your subject.

00:56:07.360 --> 00:56:11.360
[Guest]: He cannot be seen seated next to you because to sit next to somebody signifies equality.

00:56:11.360 --> 00:56:13.200
[Guest]: The queen's husband has no right to sit next to her.

00:56:13.200 --> 00:56:15.360
[Guest]: He has to follow in a smaller car.

00:56:15.360 --> 00:56:17.680
[Guest]: Back in the day, you know, they were not allowed to live in the same palace.

00:56:17.680 --> 00:56:21.600
[Guest]: The queen's husbands lived in these smaller bungalows really attached to the palace and

00:56:21.600 --> 00:56:24.560
[Guest]: they were summoned to the royal bedchamber whenever the queens wished and that was the

00:56:24.560 --> 00:56:26.760
[Guest]: arrangement.

00:56:26.760 --> 00:56:31.080
[Guest]: Usually after marriage, etc., even when they had, you know, let's use the polite word of

00:56:31.080 --> 00:56:35.240
[Guest]: sexual Congress, even when they had to sleep with each other because astrologers who decided

00:56:35.240 --> 00:56:38.040
[Guest]: when Shani was in the right place and Venus was in the right place and things like that.

00:56:38.040 --> 00:56:39.040
[Amit Varma]: The consummation of the wedding, basically.

00:56:39.040 --> 00:56:42.920
[Guest]: Yeah, the consummation of the wedding and, you know, for the initial phase so that you

00:56:42.920 --> 00:56:44.860
[Guest]: make sure a good heir is born.

00:56:44.860 --> 00:56:46.640
[Guest]: These husbands were not allowed to die in the palace.

00:56:46.640 --> 00:56:49.000
[Guest]: You know, only members of the royal family can die in the palace.

00:56:49.000 --> 00:56:50.640
[Guest]: Husbands are not members of the royal family.

00:56:50.640 --> 00:56:54.480
[Guest]: So usually if they're dying, they could even be lifted with their deathbed and taken to

00:56:54.480 --> 00:56:58.320
[Guest]: die elsewhere in a public building or a private building of their own, not in the palace.

00:56:58.320 --> 00:57:02.000
[Guest]: And the wife and the children, the Maharani and her children will not attend the man's

00:57:02.000 --> 00:57:03.000
[Guest]: funeral.

00:57:03.000 --> 00:57:04.000
[Guest]: He may be your father.

00:57:04.000 --> 00:57:07.600
[Guest]: He may be your husband, but he's a subject of the state and royalty does not attend the

00:57:07.600 --> 00:57:10.160
[Guest]: funerals of private citizens of the state.

00:57:10.160 --> 00:57:11.600
[Guest]: That is how the system works.

00:57:11.600 --> 00:57:16.080
[Guest]: For Maharaja's wives also, the amichis, they are technically private citizens of the state.

00:57:16.080 --> 00:57:19.640
[Guest]: They are wives of the Maharaja and many Maharajas are deeply in love with their wives.

00:57:19.640 --> 00:57:22.080
[Guest]: There's one who died in the mid-19th century.

00:57:22.080 --> 00:57:23.120
[Guest]: Technically his wife was a nobody.

00:57:23.120 --> 00:57:24.960
[Guest]: She has no state recognition.

00:57:24.960 --> 00:57:30.120
[Guest]: She has some pensions and honors, etc., but she has no official recognition from the Darbar

00:57:30.120 --> 00:57:31.440
[Guest]: as a member of the royal family.

00:57:31.440 --> 00:57:34.880
[Guest]: But when she dies, this man starts fasting and doing lots of religious ceremonies, etc.

00:57:34.880 --> 00:57:39.000
[Guest]: And three months later, he himself dies because this is all too much for him to take.

00:57:39.000 --> 00:57:44.680
[Guest]: You know, there's another Raja whose first wife dies very young in childbirth and this

00:57:44.680 --> 00:57:48.960
[Guest]: man for the next 17-18 years, he doesn't marry because he can't somehow give up the memory

00:57:48.960 --> 00:57:50.560
[Guest]: of his first wife.

00:57:50.560 --> 00:57:54.460
[Guest]: Legally and technically in the official documents, the Maharaja has no wife.

00:57:54.460 --> 00:57:56.320
[Guest]: Even the ritual of marriage.

00:57:56.320 --> 00:57:59.720
[Guest]: In Kerala among matrilineal communities, all you have to do is hand over a cloth.

00:57:59.720 --> 00:58:03.840
[Guest]: You light a lamp, put a red silk and a cloth, a munda, and you hand it over to the lady.

00:58:03.840 --> 00:58:05.160
[Guest]: If she accepts, you're married.

00:58:05.160 --> 00:58:07.680
[Guest]: If she throws it in your face, you're not married and divorce is very easy.

00:58:07.680 --> 00:58:11.320
[Guest]: All you have to do is, frankly, my ex-boss got in trouble for saying this, but it is

00:58:11.320 --> 00:58:14.560
[Guest]: often said in Naya families that to tell a husband not to come back, all you have to

00:58:14.560 --> 00:58:18.680
[Guest]: do is keep his things outside and, you know, keep his shoes outside or keep his spittoon

00:58:18.680 --> 00:58:21.200
[Guest]: outside or his walking stick outside and he gets the clue.

00:58:21.200 --> 00:58:22.200
[Guest]: Don't come back to this house.

00:58:22.200 --> 00:58:25.200
[Guest]: That is as simple as divorce gets.

00:58:25.200 --> 00:58:29.240
[Guest]: So there was this, what was the point I was making though?

00:58:29.240 --> 00:58:30.240
[Amit Varma]: We were talking about matrilineal.

00:58:30.240 --> 00:58:31.880
[Amit Varma]: I know, even the ritual of wedding.

00:58:31.880 --> 00:58:35.960
[Guest]: So when the kings get married, what happens is the lady is invited to the palace and there's

00:58:35.960 --> 00:58:38.440
[Guest]: a room where the wedding takes place.

00:58:38.440 --> 00:58:42.760
[Guest]: There's a cloth and it's kept in a tray and there's a golden cup that's kept there with

00:58:42.760 --> 00:58:43.760
[Guest]: water.

00:58:43.760 --> 00:58:47.520
[Guest]: And what happens is the actual handing of the cloth is done by the Chamberlain.

00:58:47.520 --> 00:58:49.160
[Guest]: It's not done by the king in person.

00:58:49.160 --> 00:58:50.680
[Guest]: The Chamberlain hands over the cloth.

00:58:50.680 --> 00:58:53.320
[Guest]: The lady wears all these fine silks and etc.

00:58:53.320 --> 00:58:56.940
[Guest]: She takes that golden pot of water and then goes into the king's bedchamber.

00:58:56.940 --> 00:59:00.520
[Guest]: So one could argue that technically she's not even married to the king because the king

00:59:00.520 --> 00:59:02.080
[Guest]: is like a saintly figure.

00:59:02.080 --> 00:59:05.840
[Guest]: There is this one historian of Travancore who talks about how Marthandavarma, because he

00:59:05.840 --> 00:59:09.560
[Guest]: creates all this protocol around the royal family and most importantly, he dedicates

00:59:09.560 --> 00:59:10.840
[Guest]: the kingdom to God.

00:59:10.840 --> 00:59:14.760
[Guest]: He goes to the Padmanabhaswamy temple and says all my conquests are dedicated to God.

00:59:14.760 --> 00:59:18.380
[Guest]: It is often cast as this great spiritual act, but it wasn't a spiritual act.

00:59:18.380 --> 00:59:20.080
[Guest]: What he was doing was again politics.

00:59:20.080 --> 00:59:22.520
[Guest]: I mean, there may have been some spiritual angle to it, but look at this.

00:59:22.520 --> 00:59:23.520
[Guest]: He was a conqueror.

00:59:23.520 --> 00:59:26.280
[Guest]: He was seen as an invader in other parts of Kerala.

00:59:26.280 --> 00:59:30.640
[Guest]: Everywhere he goes, even after he's got the heart power, people treat him with illegitimacy.

00:59:30.640 --> 00:59:32.320
[Guest]: They say you don't belong here.

00:59:32.320 --> 00:59:33.640
[Guest]: We don't accept you.

00:59:33.640 --> 00:59:35.320
[Guest]: So you donate it to God.

00:59:35.320 --> 00:59:39.600
[Guest]: You can criticize the king, but tomorrow onwards, once it becomes God's estate, you can't criticize

00:59:39.600 --> 00:59:40.600
[Guest]: God.

00:59:40.600 --> 00:59:43.680
[Guest]: So that's why by handing it over to the deity in the temple and ruling as the deity's regent

00:59:43.680 --> 00:59:48.240
[Guest]: on earth, you're basically precluding a lot of criticism.

00:59:48.240 --> 00:59:49.440
[Guest]: Nobody can stand up to you.

00:59:49.440 --> 00:59:50.960
[Guest]: It was the anti-national of its own time.

00:59:50.960 --> 00:59:53.640
[Guest]: If you stand up to the king, you're actually standing up to God.

00:59:53.640 --> 00:59:57.320
[Guest]: You're not a good citizen of the state, etc, etc.

00:59:57.320 --> 01:00:01.400
[Guest]: So you know, he reinforces this because of which the king starts being, to quote this

01:00:01.400 --> 01:00:05.520
[Guest]: historian, Sanguni Menon of the 19th century, who was a Darbar historian, the king is seen

01:00:05.520 --> 01:00:09.360
[Guest]: a lot like the Pope, the semi-religious figure.

01:00:09.360 --> 01:00:12.440
[Guest]: So the semi-religious figure is not technically supposed to have marriage and kids and carnal

01:00:12.440 --> 01:00:13.440
[Guest]: feelings.

01:00:13.440 --> 01:00:15.040
[Guest]: So there is a little bit of that also.

01:00:15.040 --> 01:00:20.040
[Guest]: But yeah, this matrilineal system, it spreads even in regular, you know, Naya families like

01:00:20.040 --> 01:00:23.800
[Guest]: mine, for example, in the old days, when my father passed away, you know, there is that

01:00:23.800 --> 01:00:27.080
[Guest]: question of whether I should even have done the rituals because his sister's children

01:00:27.080 --> 01:00:29.120
[Guest]: are the ones who have the first claim.

01:00:29.120 --> 01:00:31.000
[Guest]: Nowadays, the children do it themselves.

01:00:31.000 --> 01:00:34.160
[Guest]: But even then, somebody from the sister's family will stand with you and they will also

01:00:34.160 --> 01:00:39.120
[Guest]: participate in the ritual because that you can't entirely give up that old custom either.

01:00:39.120 --> 01:00:42.280
[Guest]: And you know, when people die, you have that period of pollution that you're not supposed

01:00:42.280 --> 01:00:46.520
[Guest]: to go to temples for a certain number of days, 10 days or 12 days or something.

01:00:46.520 --> 01:00:49.960
[Guest]: Technically, for a man's children, they don't, they're never polluted.

01:00:49.960 --> 01:00:52.800
[Guest]: The day of our father passed away, you can go to the temple if you want, because you

01:00:52.800 --> 01:00:56.640
[Guest]: don't get that pollution that goes to a sister's family, they are the ones who are polluted,

01:00:56.640 --> 01:00:57.640
[Amit Varma]: not you.

01:00:57.640 --> 01:01:02.040
[Amit Varma]: No, and one interesting consequence of matrilineal system, and I'm guessing that there is causation

01:01:02.040 --> 01:01:08.980
[Amit Varma]: to this and not just correlation, is that the women therefore tend to be extremely empowered

01:01:08.980 --> 01:01:13.040
[Amit Varma]: in the sense I was, you know, just a couple of days ago, I was reading a biography of

01:01:13.040 --> 01:01:17.040
[Amit Varma]: Mary Shelley, who wrote Frankenstein, because I was sort of talking about that for my other

01:01:17.040 --> 01:01:18.920
[Amit Varma]: show, The Book Club and Storytell.

01:01:18.920 --> 01:01:22.840
[Amit Varma]: And interesting tidbit I picked up there is that her husband Percy gave her a book to

01:01:22.840 --> 01:01:25.640
[Amit Varma]: read, which was by this guy called James Lawrence.

01:01:25.640 --> 01:01:28.000
[Amit Varma]: And it was called the Empire of the Nairs.

01:01:28.000 --> 01:01:32.240
[Amit Varma]: And she was, yeah, and Mary Shelley, you got to remember, is a daughter of Mary Wollstonecraft.

01:01:32.240 --> 01:01:34.040
[Amit Varma]: She's a feminist herself and all that.

01:01:34.040 --> 01:01:36.320
[Amit Varma]: But this book was too feminist for her.

01:01:36.320 --> 01:01:41.000
[Amit Varma]: So you know, because what the book describes and what the Nairs were and what Kerala society

01:01:41.000 --> 01:01:46.880
[Amit Varma]: was, is not just a matrilineal line of descent and, you know, giving kingship and property

01:01:46.880 --> 01:01:47.880
[Amit Varma]: and all of that.

01:01:47.880 --> 01:01:51.440
[Amit Varma]: But you know, women were empowered, they would take multiple husbands, they would, you know,

01:01:51.440 --> 01:01:53.000
[Amit Varma]: have multiple sexual partners.

01:01:53.000 --> 01:01:58.080
[Amit Varma]: And, you know, all of those, what we tend to think of as sanskar or whatever is actually

01:01:58.080 --> 01:02:02.200
[Amit Varma]: something that was brought in by the British when they impose the Victorian values.

01:02:02.200 --> 01:02:07.240
[Amit Varma]: I mean, as you've pointed out, in the last episode we did, women in Kerala typically

01:02:07.240 --> 01:02:12.880
[Amit Varma]: went around bare chested till the British, you know, impose their sense of shame on them.

01:02:12.880 --> 01:02:16.440
[Guest]: And it was in fact considered rude to, it was considered indecent, not even rude.

01:02:16.440 --> 01:02:20.600
[Guest]: You were considered a, I mean, not to use, pardon my French, but you know, you were considered

01:02:20.600 --> 01:02:21.600
[Guest]: a slut if you wore a blouse.

01:02:21.600 --> 01:02:24.640
[Guest]: If you're a Hindu woman of high caste, and you wore a blouse, they'd say, my God, why

01:02:24.640 --> 01:02:26.160
[Guest]: you dress like a slut?

01:02:26.160 --> 01:02:30.360
[Guest]: Because only a woman of no culture, only a public woman would feel the need to sort of

01:02:30.360 --> 01:02:31.360
[Guest]: cover herself up like that.

01:02:31.360 --> 01:02:34.400
[Guest]: No decent woman would feel the need to cover herself, because what are you, why are you

01:02:34.400 --> 01:02:35.400
[Guest]: sexualizing your breasts?

01:02:35.400 --> 01:02:38.720
[Amit Varma]: In fact, if I'm not mistaken, there is an anecdote in Ivory Throne also where a queen

01:02:38.720 --> 01:02:42.120
[Amit Varma]: has a woman who dares to cover her breast in front of her, has her breast mutilated.

01:02:42.120 --> 01:02:43.120
[Guest]: Yeah, there is a story.

01:02:43.120 --> 01:02:46.440
[Guest]: Because she's like, hey, we are all, you know, yeah, you can't go and you can't go and dress

01:02:46.440 --> 01:02:47.440
[Guest]: like that.

01:02:47.440 --> 01:02:48.440
[Guest]: How shameless.

01:02:48.440 --> 01:02:49.520
[Guest]: But the polyandry is fascinating.

01:02:49.520 --> 01:02:53.200
[Guest]: This idea of women having multiple husbands, as I said, not only divorce, but you could

01:02:53.200 --> 01:02:54.200
[Guest]: have multiple husbands.

01:02:54.200 --> 01:02:57.440
[Guest]: I have met a woman, she's still alive, there's a town called Mamalikara, there's a village

01:02:57.440 --> 01:02:59.960
[Guest]: near that, which is where my ancestors lived.

01:02:59.960 --> 01:03:03.360
[Guest]: And in that village, I met a woman in her 90s, who was married to two brothers.

01:03:03.360 --> 01:03:05.240
[Guest]: She was co-wife to two brothers.

01:03:05.240 --> 01:03:06.240
[Guest]: And this woman is still alive.

01:03:06.240 --> 01:03:07.240
[Guest]: I have spoken to her.

01:03:07.240 --> 01:03:08.240
[Guest]: I've talked to her.

01:03:08.240 --> 01:03:09.920
[Guest]: And of course, it's very awkward to raise this question.

01:03:09.920 --> 01:03:13.840
[Guest]: But everybody in that village openly says that madams, you know, they refer to the senior

01:03:13.840 --> 01:03:17.520
[Guest]: husband, the junior husband based on the on the age of these two men who are brothers.

01:03:17.520 --> 01:03:19.120
[Guest]: And there is no embarrassment about it.

01:03:19.120 --> 01:03:23.560
[Guest]: You know, there is a maid says, avrte valya saar and kocha saar, saar is the English word

01:03:23.560 --> 01:03:26.440
[Guest]: sir, and kocha and valya means junior and senior.

01:03:26.440 --> 01:03:27.440
[Guest]: There is no embarrassment.

01:03:27.440 --> 01:03:31.280
[Guest]: There is no sense of surprise, because these things are not all that unfamiliar.

01:03:31.280 --> 01:03:35.520
[Guest]: We like to pretend now, we like to pretend that there is something taboo about this.

01:03:35.520 --> 01:03:39.800
[Guest]: But the fact is, in rural Kerala, this sort of story is still, it doesn't startle anyone.

01:03:39.800 --> 01:03:42.880
[Guest]: There are still families, there are still old people who've lived that life, who've

01:03:42.880 --> 01:03:45.840
[Guest]: lived in that polyandrous system.

01:03:45.840 --> 01:03:48.800
[Guest]: My great grandmother, there's a wonderful story about how she first started wearing

01:03:48.800 --> 01:03:49.800
[Guest]: the blouse.

01:03:49.800 --> 01:03:51.120
[Guest]: This is only in the 1940s.

01:03:51.120 --> 01:03:55.040
[Guest]: She's already a woman in her 40s at that time, her second daughter gets married, and the

01:03:55.040 --> 01:03:57.680
[Guest]: younger women are also wearing blouses and saris, etc.

01:03:57.680 --> 01:04:01.120
[Guest]: They've stopped giving, they've given up the older tradition of wearing just the thing

01:04:01.120 --> 01:04:02.600
[Guest]: around your waist.

01:04:02.600 --> 01:04:07.080
[Guest]: So for the wedding, the boy's mother comes to the house, and she brings with her and

01:04:07.080 --> 01:04:09.000
[Guest]: she's come wearing this thing called the rauka.

01:04:09.000 --> 01:04:11.280
[Guest]: And my great grandmother is like, my God, you're my age, but you're wearing a blouse

01:04:11.280 --> 01:04:12.280
[Guest]: and all that.

01:04:12.280 --> 01:04:15.280
[Guest]: And she says, well, don't you know, this is a new fashion, you know, it's 1940s now such

01:04:15.280 --> 01:04:18.800
[Guest]: a modern time, we should start wearing these, these, you know, wonderful new things called

01:04:18.800 --> 01:04:19.800
[Guest]: blouses.

01:04:19.800 --> 01:04:23.000
[Guest]: And my great grandmother wears it and first she's extremely ashamed about coming out in

01:04:23.000 --> 01:04:24.000
[Guest]: public wearing it.

01:04:24.000 --> 01:04:26.960
[Guest]: So she'll wear it inside the house, show it to her daughters and hide it and fold it away

01:04:26.960 --> 01:04:27.960
[Guest]: and put it away.

01:04:27.960 --> 01:04:30.520
[Guest]: Thinking, oh my God, if I wear a blouse, what will my husband say?

01:04:30.520 --> 01:04:31.520
[Guest]: What will my brother say?

01:04:31.520 --> 01:04:35.680
[Guest]: You know, how indecent of me to do that, what will they think about me and so on.

01:04:35.680 --> 01:04:39.600
[Guest]: Finally takes her children sometime to persuade her saying that it's okay to wear a blouse.

01:04:39.600 --> 01:04:41.360
[Guest]: Wearing a blouse does not make you a bad person.

01:04:41.360 --> 01:04:44.880
[Guest]: You know, this is a time where she belongs to that generation of wearing a blouse is

01:04:44.880 --> 01:04:45.880
[Guest]: a bad thing.

01:04:45.880 --> 01:04:48.800
[Guest]: My father's side great grandmother till she died in the 1970s.

01:04:48.800 --> 01:04:49.800
[Guest]: She never wore a blouse.

01:04:49.800 --> 01:04:50.800
[Guest]: She refused.

01:04:50.800 --> 01:04:51.800
[Guest]: She said, I will not dress like this.

01:04:51.800 --> 01:04:55.320
[Guest]: This new newfangled fashion that you guys have discovered, I'm not going to wear it.

01:04:55.320 --> 01:04:58.640
[Guest]: So we have a photograph of her taken on one of those old cameras where you get these square

01:04:58.640 --> 01:05:01.800
[Guest]: little pictures of her with a niece of hers or something.

01:05:01.800 --> 01:05:05.600
[Guest]: The niece is wearing a blouse and a regular Majali saree as it were.

01:05:05.600 --> 01:05:09.200
[Guest]: The old lady's just got a loose cloth on one side of her shoulder.

01:05:09.200 --> 01:05:11.560
[Guest]: So the other side is completely exposed and she's got this.

01:05:11.560 --> 01:05:16.720
[Guest]: And my father says that it was, I mean, people didn't even look at it as bad or as something

01:05:16.720 --> 01:05:18.040
[Guest]: to be embarrassed about.

01:05:18.040 --> 01:05:20.640
[Guest]: That woman would, you know, people would come to the house, she would feed them.

01:05:20.640 --> 01:05:22.720
[Guest]: She would have servants around the house.

01:05:22.720 --> 01:05:24.120
[Guest]: This is an agrarian society.

01:05:24.120 --> 01:05:27.880
[Guest]: So a lot of workers would be around and she'd be the one managing all this in the stopless

01:05:27.880 --> 01:05:31.640
[Guest]: avatar because nobody looked at it with that sexual gaze.

01:05:31.640 --> 01:05:36.800
[Guest]: Nobody looked at it with a gaze of that conveyed vulgarity or indecency in any way.

01:05:36.800 --> 01:05:38.600
[Guest]: But these things can change very quickly, right?

01:05:38.600 --> 01:05:39.640
[Guest]: That's the thing with sanskar.

01:05:39.640 --> 01:05:42.600
[Guest]: Often things we think are ancient sanskar are not all that ancient.

01:05:42.600 --> 01:05:44.160
[Guest]: They're a very recent vintage.

01:05:44.160 --> 01:05:47.680
[Amit Varma]: No, in fact, and that's probably the worst thing the British gave us this whole veneer

01:05:47.680 --> 01:05:52.800
[Amit Varma]: of morality, which you put on everything and I think of, you know, we might be the most

01:05:52.800 --> 01:05:57.320
[Amit Varma]: if not one of the most sexually repressed nations on earth and a lot of it is, you know,

01:05:57.320 --> 01:05:59.120
[Guest]: because of shit like this, which the British brought in.

01:05:59.120 --> 01:06:00.120
[Guest]: We weren't like this.

01:06:00.120 --> 01:06:03.960
[Guest]: We internalized a lot of their, you know, the British started calling us uncivilized.

01:06:03.960 --> 01:06:04.960
[Guest]: They started calling us barbaric.

01:06:04.960 --> 01:06:06.440
[Guest]: They said, Oh, you don't even cover yourself.

01:06:06.440 --> 01:06:07.920
[Guest]: And what is this like hideous culture?

01:06:07.920 --> 01:06:11.640
[Guest]: And how can you be so proud of your culture if this is how you even walk around?

01:06:11.640 --> 01:06:16.520
[Guest]: You know, there's this, I was reading a review yesterday of a book on the Devdasi Balasaraswati.

01:06:16.520 --> 01:06:19.840
[Guest]: And it's fascinating that in the review, it's not in the book, I think, but in the review,

01:06:19.840 --> 01:06:23.600
[Guest]: the critic talks about how there was a famous Devdasi who would perform and these men would

01:06:23.600 --> 01:06:29.240
[Guest]: gather around and one of her acts was to pretend she had lost her hearing and look for it basically

01:06:29.240 --> 01:06:33.240
[Guest]: in the crotches of all these men who would gather and they'd all laugh, etc, etc.

01:06:33.240 --> 01:06:38.240
[Guest]: It was sort of vulgar in some ways, perhaps it was some sort of playful, sexual, whatever.

01:06:38.240 --> 01:06:40.960
[Guest]: But we were a culture that even had that.

01:06:40.960 --> 01:06:45.000
[Guest]: And these patrons of Devdasi were all who big temple Brahmins, big landlords, people

01:06:45.000 --> 01:06:46.000
[Guest]: like that.

01:06:46.000 --> 01:06:49.120
[Guest]: And they were basically saying that Indian culture included landlords gathering around

01:06:49.120 --> 01:06:51.560
[Guest]: a woman looking for her hearing in their crotch.

01:06:51.560 --> 01:06:52.560
[Guest]: That was permissible.

01:06:52.560 --> 01:06:55.680
[Guest]: That's there were spaces to allow even something like that.

01:06:55.680 --> 01:06:58.760
[Guest]: Now, we're not getting into the politics of whether it was good for the Devdasi, whether

01:06:58.760 --> 01:07:00.280
[Guest]: you know, it was good for women and so on.

01:07:00.280 --> 01:07:03.640
[Guest]: But the point is, there were cultural spaces where there's that kind of sexual liberation.

01:07:03.640 --> 01:07:06.840
[Amit Varma]: And at least to my limited knowledge, Devdasi weren't slut shamed.

01:07:06.840 --> 01:07:09.640
[Guest]: It wasn't, you know, it was a later equation of Devdasi.

01:07:09.640 --> 01:07:11.840
[Amit Varma]: Slut shaming also is because of Victorian.

01:07:11.840 --> 01:07:16.360
[Guest]: Victorians not only depose Rajas, which means what the patronage that Devdasi has received

01:07:16.360 --> 01:07:19.440
[Guest]: is gone suddenly from doing poetry and literature, etc.

01:07:19.440 --> 01:07:23.360
[Guest]: Many of them are forced to actually get into prostitution, because they have to survive.

01:07:23.360 --> 01:07:24.560
[Guest]: There is obviously prostitution.

01:07:24.560 --> 01:07:27.840
[Guest]: One can't say that they weren't coerced and their bodies weren't used by men.

01:07:27.840 --> 01:07:30.120
[Guest]: But equally, it wasn't like they were without agency.

01:07:30.120 --> 01:07:34.000
[Guest]: A lot of these women did have agency, a lot of the women were beyond, a random man couldn't

01:07:34.000 --> 01:07:35.000
[Guest]: go and grasp them.

01:07:35.000 --> 01:07:37.960
[Guest]: They chose their patrons if they were in positions of power.

01:07:37.960 --> 01:07:43.120
[Guest]: And there are cases of Devdasi in positions of great power and great literature, in places

01:07:43.120 --> 01:07:46.520
[Guest]: of great literary quality and great literary achievement.

01:07:46.520 --> 01:07:49.760
[Guest]: We discussed Muddu Parini, for example, in our last session on my third book.

01:07:49.760 --> 01:07:52.040
[Guest]: So, you know, there are there are stories like that.

01:07:52.040 --> 01:07:56.160
[Guest]: But the point is, for a culture now where men go into clubs and beat up women for wearing

01:07:56.160 --> 01:07:57.160
[Guest]: short clothes.

01:07:57.160 --> 01:08:00.160
[Guest]: Hello, talk about this Devdasi who's looking for a earring in somebody's crotch.

01:08:00.160 --> 01:08:03.880
[Guest]: She was, you know, part of India's tradition, as it were.

01:08:03.880 --> 01:08:06.560
[Guest]: Tradition is not a rock, as I, you know, that's my latest analogy.

01:08:06.560 --> 01:08:09.320
[Guest]: It's not a rock you put in a gilded cage and try to protect.

01:08:09.320 --> 01:08:10.320
[Guest]: It's a breathing organism.

01:08:10.320 --> 01:08:14.720
[Guest]: It has it has an amorphous shape, you know, it is a shapeless commodity, frankly, just

01:08:14.720 --> 01:08:19.960
[Guest]: keeps evolving and changing with time, acquiring different hues based on what we make of it.

01:08:19.960 --> 01:08:24.160
[Guest]: So to think that, you know, our culture is some kind of stayed sedate thing where everyone's

01:08:24.160 --> 01:08:27.240
[Guest]: got their spines erect and they're wearing starched clothes and chanting the thousand

01:08:27.240 --> 01:08:28.800
[Guest]: names of Vishnu every day.

01:08:28.800 --> 01:08:29.800
[Guest]: Not true.

01:08:29.800 --> 01:08:33.840
[Guest]: There is there is a culture far beyond this textbook version, which the Victorians and

01:08:33.840 --> 01:08:38.760
[Guest]: the 19th century so-called reformers popularized and Kerala fell victim to this in a very major

01:08:38.760 --> 01:08:42.640
[Guest]: way because the matrilineal system completely shocked all these people, polyandry shocked

01:08:42.640 --> 01:08:43.860
[Guest]: them even more.

01:08:43.860 --> 01:08:49.200
[Guest]: And perhaps the idea of women holding property got even more scandalizing for a lot of men.

01:08:49.200 --> 01:08:50.920
[Amit Varma]: And in your book, of course, is all this and more.

01:08:50.920 --> 01:08:54.000
[Amit Varma]: And the interesting thing about your book is that it's more than 700 pages.

01:08:54.000 --> 01:08:56.480
[Amit Varma]: It's 20 chapters and a preface.

01:08:56.480 --> 01:08:58.840
[Amit Varma]: And we've just finished talking about the preface.

